name: cleaving embryo
description: Organism at the cleavage stage.

name: sexually immature organism
description: A multicellular organism that is at the juvenile stage.
parents: RO:0000086 some PATO:0001190|RO:0002489 some UBERON:0000112|RO:0002493 some UBERON:0000112|UBERON:0000468

name: adult organism
description: A multicellular organism that existence_ends_with a post-juvenile adult stage and existence_starts_with a post-juvenile adult stage.

name: chordo neural hinge
description: Portion of tissue that is posterior to the developing notochord during tail bud extension.

name: mandibular neural crest
description: Cranial neural crest that migrates into the mandibular arch.

name: hyoid neural crest
description: Cranial neural crest that migrates into the hyoid arch.

name: primary circulatory organ
description: A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood or analogs[GO,modified].

name: vitelline duct
description: A long narrow tube that joins the yolk-sac to the midgut lumen of the developing fetus.

name: chorionic villus
description: One of the minute vascular projections of the fetal chorion that combines with maternal uterine tissue to form the placenta.

name: vernix caseosa
description: An unctuous substance composed of sebum and desquamated epithelial cells, which covers the skin of the fetus.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000323|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0001866|CARO:0000000|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0003055|RO:0002221 some UBERON:0002097|UBERON:0000456

name: meconium
description: A dark greenish mass that accumulates in the bowel during fetal life and is discharged shortly after birth.

name: Douglas' pouch
description: The rectouterine pouch (or rectouterine excavation, rectovaginal, Ehrhardt-Cole Recess or Pouch of Douglas) is the extension of the peritoneal cavity between the rectum and back wall of the uterus in the female human body. The rectouterine pouch is used in the treatment of end-stage renal failure in patients who are treated by peritoneal dialysis. The tip of the dialysis catheter is placed into the deepest point of the pouch. In women it is the deepest point of the peritoneal cavity, posterior to (behind) the uterus and anterior to (in front of) rectum. (The pouch on the other side of the uterus is the vesicouterine excavation. ) It is near the posterior fornix of the vagina. In men, the region corresponding to the rectouterine pouch is the rectovesical excavation, which lies between the urinary bladder and rectum. (There is no equivalent to the vesicouterine excavation.).

name: venom
description: Poisonous animal secretions forming fluid mixtures of many different enzymes, toxins, and other substances. These substances are produced in specialized glands and secreted through specialized delivery systems (nematocysts, spines, fangs, etc.) for disabling prey or predator.

name: deciduous tooth
description: One of the first set of teeth in the growth development of humans and many other mammals[WP].

name: primary dentition
description: The set of teeth first in order or time of development that will be replaced by permanent dentition upon their loss.

name: umbilicus
description: The pit in the center of the abdominal wall marking the point where the umbilical cord entered in the fetus.

name: neck of femur
description: The femur neck or neck of the femur is a flattened pyramidal process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft, and forming with the latter a wide angle opening medialward.

name: premolar tooth
description: The premolar teeth or bicuspids are transitional teeth located between the canine and molar teeth.

name: skin nerve field
description: A zone of skin that is mainly innervated by a single sensory nerve. A nerve field innervated by exactly one dorsal root is called a dermatome.

name: pharyngeal pouch 1
description: A pharyngeal pouch that is between pharyngeal arches 1 and 2.

name: pharyngeal pouch 2
description: A pharyngeal puch that is between the pharyngeal arches 2 and 3.

name: pharyngeal pouch 3
description: A pharyngeal pouch that between pharyngeal arches 3 and 4.

name: pharyngeal pouch 4
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arch 4 and arch 5 or 6 (a fifth arch never establishes in amniotes).

name: pharyngeal pouch 5
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arches 5 and 6.

name: pharyngeal pouch 6
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arches 6 and 7.

name: glomeral mesenchyme
description: Portion of tissue that consists of the precursors of the pronephric glomus or glomerulus; derived from the medial portion of the pronephric intermediate mesoderm.

name: head kidney
description: Teleost head kidney consists of fused bilateral lobes located in the anterior part of the kidney. It is analogous to the mammalian bone marrow and the primary site of definitive hematopoiesis[ZFA,modified].
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000949|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002113|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002390|BFO:0000067 some GO:0030097|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0002120|UBERON:0003103|UBERON:0004177|UBERON:0005172

name: trunk ganglion
description: Ganglion which is located in the trunk.

name: neural keel
description: An intermediate stage (between the neural plate and neural rod) during the early segmentation period in the morphogenesis of the central nervous system primordium; the keel is roughly triangular shaped in cross section.

name: rectouterine fold
description: These folds of the rectouterine excavation are named the sacrogenital or rectouterine folds. They contain a considerable amount of fibrous tissue and non-striped muscular fibers which are attached to the front of the sacrum and constitute the uterosacral ligaments.

name: parietal mesothelium
description: Mesothelium overs the body walls is called the parietal mesothelium.

name: visceral mesothelium
description: Mesothelium that covers the internal organs is called visceral mesothelium.

name: left internal carotid artery
description: An internal carotid artery that branching_part_of a left common carotid artery plus branches.

name: right internal carotid artery
description: An internal carotid artery that branching_part_of a right common carotid artery plus branches.

name: embryonic post-anal tail
description: An embryonic structure that will either develop into a post-anal tail or recede into a vestigial remnant of the tail.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000922|CARO:0000000|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0002533|RO:0002494 some UBERON:0002533|UBERON:0002050

name: posterior spinal artery
description: A spinal artery that arises from the vertebral artery, adjacent to the medulla oblongata[WP,modified].

name: lumen of midgut
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a midgut.

name: lumen of hindgut
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a hindgut.

name: inferior thyroid artery
description: One of the three branches of the thyroid axis that supplies the thyroid gland and branches to form the ascending cervical, esophageal, inferior laryngeal, muscular and tracheal arteries.

name: superior thyroid artery
description: The superior thyroid artery arises from the external carotid artery just below the level of the greater cornu of the hyoid bone and ends in the thyroid gland.

name: mitral valve leaflet
description: A valve leafleft that is part of a mitral valve.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002135|CARO:0000003|RO:0002371 some UBERON:0005995|RO:0002371 some UBERON:0014851|UBERON:0011741

name: inferior sagittal sinus
description: An intracranial venous sinus that lies in a midline location along the lower free border of the falx cerebri of the brain. The sinus receives blood from the great cerebral vein and joins the superior sagittal sinus posteriorly.

name: superior epigastric artery
description: An artery that arises from the internal thoracic arteryand anastomoses with the inferior epigastric artery at the umbilicus and supplies the anterior part of the abdominal wall and some of the diaphragm.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002456|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0002456|UBERON:0004573|UBERON:0006349|obo:uberon/core#anastomoses_with some UBERON:0001354

name: inferior epigastric vein
description: The blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood that arises from the superior epigastric vein and empties into the external iliac vein.

name: superior epigastric vein
description: A vein that drains into the internal thoracic vein, anastomosing with the inferior epigastric vein at the level of the umbilicus and drains the anterior part of the abdominal wall and some of the diaphragm. Along its course, it is accompanied by a similarly named artery, the superior epigastric artery.

name: inferior thyroid vein
description: The inferior thyroid veins two, frequently three or four, in number, arise in the venous plexus on the thyroid gland, communicating with the middle and superior thyroid veins. They form a plexus in front of the trachea, behind the Sternothyreoidei. From this plexus, a left vein descends and joins the left innominate trunk, and a right vein passes obliquely downward and to the right across the innominate artery to open into the right innominate vein, just at its junction with the superior vena cava; sometimes the right and left veins open by a common trunk in the latter situation. These veins receive esophageal tracheal, and inferior laryngeal veins, and are provided with valves at their terminations in the innominate veins.

name: superior thyroid vein
description: The superior thyroid vein begins in the substance and on the surface of the thyroid gland, by tributaries corresponding with the branches of the superior thyroid artery, and ends in the upper part of the internal jugular vein. It receives the superior laryngeal and cricothyroid veins.

name: lumen of anal canal
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a anal canal.

name: lumen of colon
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a colon.

name: inferior petrosal sinus
description: The inferior petrosal sinus, within the human head, is an area beneath the brain, which allows blood veins to span the area, from the center of the head downward. It drains from the cavernous sinus (beneath the brain) to the sigmoid sinuses above the internal jugular vein.

name: medial arcuate ligament
description: The medial arcuate ligament (also medial lumbocostal arch) is tendinous fascia that arches over the psoas major muscle as it passes through the diaphragm.

name: lateral arcuate ligament
description: The lateral arcuate ligament (also lateral lumbocostal arch) is a ligament under the diaphragm that arches across the upper part of the quadratus lumborum. It is traversed by the subcostal nerve, artery and vein.

name: superior nasal meatus
description: The superior meatus, the smallest of the three meatuses of the nose, occupies the middle third of the lateral wall of the nasal cavity. It lies between the superior nasal conchC& and middle nasal conchC&; the sphenopalatine foramen opens into it behind, and the posterior ethmoidal cells in front. The sphenoidal sinus opens into a recess, the sphenoethmoidal recess, which is placed above and behind the superior concha.

name: distal radio-ulnar joint
description: The Distal Radioulnar Articulation (inferior radioulnar joint) is a pivot-joint formed between the head of the ulna and the ulnar notch on the distal radius.

name: proximal radio-ulnar joint
description: The proximal radioulnar articulation (superior radioulnar joint) is a trochoid or pivot joint between the circumference of the head of the radius and the ring formed by the radial notch of the ulna and the annular ligament.

name: long head of biceps brachii
description: The long head originates on the supraglenoid tubercle just above the shoulder joint from where its tendon passes down along the intertubercular groove of the humerus into the joint capsule of the shoulder joint. [1] When the humerus is in motion, the tendon of the long head is held firmly in place in the intertubercular groove by the greater and lesser tubercles and the overlying transverse humeral ligament. During the motion from external to internal rotation, the tendon is forced medially against the lesser tubercle and superiorly against the transverse ligament.

name: short head of biceps brachii
description: Proximally (towards the body), the short head of the biceps attaches to (originates from) the coracoid process at the top of the scapula.

name: squamous part of occipital bone
description: The squama of the occipital bone, situated above and behind the foramen magnum, is curved from above downward and from side to side.

name: lateral border of scapula
description: The lateral border (or axillary border, or margin) is the thickest of the three borders of the scapula. It begins above at the lower margin of the glenoid cavity, and inclines obliquely downward and backward to the inferior angle. Immediately below the glenoid cavity is a rough impression, the infraglenoid tuberosity, about 2.5 cm. in length, which gives origin to the long head of the Triceps brachii; in front of this is a longitudinal groove, which extends as far as the lower third of this border, and affords origin to part of the Subscapularis. The inferior third is thin and sharp, and serves for the attachment of a few fibers of the Teres major behind, and of the Subscapularis in front.

name: medial border of scapula
description: The medial border of the scapula (vertebral border, medial margin) is the longest of the three borders, and extends from the medial to the inferior angle. It is arched, intermediate in thickness between the superior and the axillary borders, and the portion of it above the spine forms an obtuse angle with the part below. This border presents an anterior and a posterior lip, and an intermediate narrow area. The anterior lip affords attachment to the Serratus anterior; the posterior lip, to the Supraspinatus above the spine, the Infraspinatus below; the area between the two lips, to the Levator scapulC& above the triangular surface at the commencement of the spine, to the Rhomboideus minor on the edge of that surface, and to the Rhomboideus major below it; this last is attached by means of a fibrous arch, connected above to the lower part of the triangular surface at the base of the spine, and below to the lower part of the border.

name: inferior angle of scapula
description: An angle of the scapula formed by the union of the vertebral and axillary borders; its dorsal surface affords attachment to the Teres major and frequently to a few fibers of the Latissimus dorsi.[WP,unvetted].

name: superior angle of scapula
description: An angle of the scapula formed by the junction of the superior and vertebral borders. It is thin, smooth, rounded, inclined somewhat lateralward, and gives attachment to a few fibers of the Levator scapulae[WP,unvetted].

name: lamina propria of mucosa of colon
description: A lamina propria that is part of a colonic mucosa.

name: muscularis mucosae of colon
description: A muscularis mucosa that is part of a colonic mucosa.

name: serosa of infundibulum of uterine tube
description: A serous membrane that is part of a uterine tube infundibulum.

name: muscle layer of infundibulum of uterine tube
description: A muscle layer that is part of a uterine tube infundibulum.

name: pericardio-peritoneal canal mesothelium
description: A mesothelium that is part of a pericardio-peritoneal canal.

name: pericardial visceral mesothelium
description: A visceral mesothelium that is part of a pericardium.

name: pericardial parietal mesothelium
description: A parietal mesothelium that is part of a pericardium.

name: mesothelium of serous pericardium
description: A mesothelium that is part of a serous pericardium.

name: orbital gyrus
description: The inferior or orbital surface of the frontal lobe is concave, and rests on the orbital plate of the frontal bone. It is divided into four orbital gyri by a well-marked H-shaped orbital sulcus. These are named, from their position, the medial, anterior, lateral, and posterior orbital gyri. The medial orbital gyrus presents a well-marked antero-posterior sulcus, the olfactory sulcus, for the olfactory tract; the portion medial to this is named the straight gyrus, and is continuous with the superior frontal gyrus on the medial surface.

name: vesicular gland
description: The vesicular gland is part of the male reproductive system. The vesicular gland contributes fluids, energy substrates, and buffers to semen. It can be found near the Coagulating gland, which also belongs to the reproductive system.

name: stroma of bone marrow
description: The stroma of the bone marrow is all tissue not directly involved in the primary function of hematopoiesis. The yellow bone marrow belongs here, and makes the majority of the bone marrow stroma, in addition to stromal cells located in the red bone marrow. Yellow bone marrow is found in the Medullary cavity. Still, the stroma is indirectly involved in hematopoiesis, since it provides the hematopoietic microenvironment that facilitates hematopoiesis by the parenchymal cells. For instance, they generate colony stimulating factors, affecting hematopoiesis.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002371|BFO:0000051 some CL:0002240|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0000332|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0003909|UBERON:0003891|UBERON:0004120

name: tracheobronchial tree
description: The structure from the trachea, bronchi, and bronchioles that forms the airways that supply air to the lungs. The lining of the tracheobronchial tree consists of ciliated columnar epithelial cells.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001558|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0002185|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0003126|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0007592|UBERON:0000062|UBERON:0004119

name: hermaphroditic organism
description: Multicellular organism that can produce both male and female gametes.

name: hermaphrodite anatomical structure
description: An anatomical structure present only in hermaphrodites.

name: mesenchyme derived from head neural crest
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a cranial neural crest.

name: mesenchyme derived from trunk neural crest
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a trunk neural crest.

name: trabecula cranii
description: Paired thin medially aligned bar of cartilage that extends from the anterior end of the chondrocranium to just anterior to the anterior end of the notochord. The posterior ends of the trabeculae cranii are continuous with the parachordal cartilages, and they enclose the hypophyseal fenestra.

name: late embryonic stage
description: An embryo stage that covers late steps of the embryogenesis with a fully formed embryo still developing before birth or egg hatching.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000068|BFO:0000062 some UBERON:0000111|BFO:0000062 some UBERON:0004707|UBERON:0000105

name: neonate stage
description: Of or pertaining to the period of time immediately following birth, or to the newborn.

name: osseus cochlea
description: The osseous cochlea is the bony foundation that forms the small shell arrangement for the cochlear nerve.

name: medial entorhinal cortex
description: One of two subdivisions of the entorhinal cortex, located medially.

name: lateral entorhinal cortex
description: One of two subdivisions of the entorhinal cortex, located laterally.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002022|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002728|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002895|UBERON:0000064|UBERON:0004121|UBERON:0010314

name: superior vestibular nucleus
description: The superior vestibular nucleus is the dorso-lateral part of the vestibular nucleus and receives collaterals and terminals from the ascending branches of the vestibular nerve. Its axons terminate in much the same manner as do those from the lateral nucleus.

name: vestibular nucleus
description: A cranial nucleus for the vestibular nerve. [WP,unvetted].
parents: BFO:0000050 some RO:0002577|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002673|UBERON:0007635|obo:uberon/core#extends_fibers_into some UBERON:0003723

name: lateral vestibular nucleus
description: One of the nuclei comprising the vestibular nuclear complex. In some mammals, e.g., primates, it is further subdivided into subnuclei. It therefore differs in appearance and topology in different mammals.

name: tunica media of artery
description: A tunica media that is part of a artery.

name: tunica adventitia of artery
description: A tunica adventitia that is part of a artery.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000415|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001637|BFO:0000051 some CL:1000306|UBERON:0005734

name: tunica adventitia of vein
description: A tunica adventitia that is part of a vein.

name: tunica intima of vein
description: A tunica intima that is part of a vein.

name: tunica media of vein
description: A tunica media that is part of a vein.

name: inferior olivary nucleus
description: The inferior olivary nucleus is the largest nucleus situated in the olivary body, part of the medulla oblongata.

name: nuclear complex of neuraxis
description: Gray matter of the central nervous system which is a collection of clustered nuclei.

name: nucleus of superior olivary complex
description: Any of the nuclei that comprise the superior olivary complex (superior olive). This includes both the primary nuclei such as the lateral and medial nuclei, as well as periolivary nuclei.

name: dorsal accessory inferior olivary nucleus
description: The inferior olivary nucleus that is the smallest, and appears on transverse section as a curved lamina behind the primary olivary nucleus.

name: lingual tonsil
description: The lymph tissue on the floor of the oropharyngeal passage, near the root of the tongue.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001723|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0010033|BSPO:0000126 some UBERON:0010033|RO:0002433 some UBERON:0001735|UBERON:0002372|UBERON:0015212

name: preoptic nucleus
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a preoptic area.

name: intervertebral disk of cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a cervical region of vertebral column. A cervical intervertebral disk connects at least one cervical vertebra, either to another cervical vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a thoracic vertebra.

name: intervertebral disk of thoracic vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a thoracic region of vertebral column. A thoracic intervertebral disk connects at least one thoracic vertebra, either to another thoracic vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a lumbar vertebra.

name: intervertebral disk of lumbar vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a lumbar region of vertebral column. A lumbar intervertebral disk connects at least one lumbar vertebra, either to another thoracic vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a sacral vertebra.

name: intervertebral disk of sacral vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a sacral region of vertebral column. A sacral intervertebral disk connects at least one sacral vertebra, either to another thoracic vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a sacral vertebra.

name: intervertebral disk of third cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 3 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 4.

name: intervertebral disk of fourth cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 4 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 5.

name: intervertebral disk of fifth cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 5 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 6.

name: intervertebral disk of sixth cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 6 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 7.

name: intervertebral disk of seventh cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a thoracic vertebra and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 7.

name: intervertebral disk of axis
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a vertebral bone 2 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 3.

name: intervertebral disk of atlas
description: An intervertebral disk that connects a vertebral bone 1 and connects a vertebral bone 2.

name: trachea pre-cartilage rings
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a trachea.

name: upper esophageal sphincter
description: The upper esophageal sphincter (UES) (also called the Pharyngoesophageal sphincter) refers to the superior portion of the esophagus. Unlike the lower esophageal sphincter, it consists of striated muscle and is under conscious control. The primary muscle of the UES is the cricopharyngeus portion of the inferior pharyngeal constrictor. During swallowing the upper esophageal sphincter opens so the bolus can pass into the esophagus. A secondary role of the UES is to reduce backflow from the esophagus into the pharynx.

name: pectoral appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: pelvic appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a pelvic appendage.

name: appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of an appendage.

name: pectoral appendage skeleton
description: Skeletal subdivision consisting of the anterior appendicular limb skeleton, excluding the pectoral girdle.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0004710|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|RO:0002576 some UBERON:0004710|UBERON:0011582

name: crista of ampulla of anterior semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a anterior semicircular duct.

name: crista of ampulla of posterior semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a posterior semicircular duct.

name: crista of ampulla of lateral semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a lateral semicircular duct.

name: presumptive hindbrain
description: The rhombencephalon (or hindbrain) is a developmental categorization of portions of the central nervous system in vertebrates. The rhombencephalon can be subdivided in a variable number of transversal swellings called rhombomeres. In the human embryo eight rhombomeres can be distinguished, from caudal to rostral: Rh7-Rh1 and the isthmus (the most rostral rhombomere). A rare disease of the rhombencephalon, 'rhombencephalosynapsis' is characterized by a missing vermis resulting in a fused cerebellum. Patients generally present with cerebellar ataxia. The caudal rhombencephalon has been generally considered as the initiation site for neural tube closure.

name: presumptive sinus venosus
description: Portion of tissue that is part of the heart tube and will become the sinus venosus.

name: presumptive atrioventricular canal
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a atrioventricular canal.

name: presumptive endocardium
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a endocardium.

name: presumptive midbrain hindbrain boundary
description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the midbrain hindbrain boundary.

name: presumptive segmental plate
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a presomitic mesoderm.

name: presumptive shield
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a primitive knot.

name: presumptive neural plate
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a neural plate.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0004734|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0002346|RO:0002387 some UBERON:0003075|UBERON:0016879

name: presumptive paraxial mesoderm
description: The part of the blastula that has the potential to develop into a paraxial mesoderm.

name: presumptive floor plate
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a floor plate.

name: presumptive bulbus arteriosus
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a bulbus arteriosus.

name: presumptive forebrain midbrain boundary
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a forebrain-midbrain boundary.

name: presumptive rhombomere 1
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 1.

name: presumptive rhombomere 3
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 3.

name: presumptive rhombomere 4
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 4.

name: presumptive rhombomere 5
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 5.

name: presumptive rhombomere 6
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 6.

name: presumptive rhombomere 7
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 7.

name: presumptive rhombomere 8
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 8.

name: presumptive rhombomere 2
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 2.

name: presumptive pronephric mesoderm
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a pronephric mesoderm.

name: pronephric proximal convoluted tubule
description: A proximal convoluted tubule that is part of a pronephros.

name: choroid plexus of tectal ventricle
description: A choroid plexus that is part of a cerebral aqueduct.

name: pectoral appendage blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: appendage blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a limb/fin.

name: pectoral appendage vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: pharyngeal vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a chordate pharynx.

name: appendage vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a limb/fin.

name: pronephric glomerular capillary
description: A glomerular capillary that is part of a pronephros.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002120|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0004739|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0005309|UBERON:0004212

name: pronephric glomerular basement membrane
description: A glomerular basement membrane that is part of a pronephros.

name: pronephric distal early tubule
description: A distal early tubule that is part of a pronephros.

name: sputum
description: Matter ejected from the lungs, bronchi, and trachea, through the mouth.

name: pudendal artery
description: Either the internal or external pudendal arteries.

name: internal pudendal artery
description: The internal pudendal artery is an artery that branches off the internal iliac artery, providing blood to the external genitalia. The internal pudendal artery is the terminal branch of the anterior trunk of the internal iliac artery. It is smaller in the female than in the male.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001309|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0006867|BSPO:0000126 some UBERON:0006867|RO:0002178 some UBERON:0004176|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0001309|UBERON:0003835|UBERON:0004573|UBERON:0007312|UBERON:0015212

name: deep external pudendal artery
description: The deep external pudendal artery (deep external pudic artery), more deeply seated than the superficial external pudendal artery, passes medialward across the Pectineus and the Adductor longus muscles; it is covered by the fascia lata, which it pierces at the medial side of the thigh, and is distributed, in the male, to the integument of the scrotum and perineum, in the female to the labium majus; its branches anastomose with the scrotal (or labial) branches of the perineal artery.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001308|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002060|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0035551|RO:0002178 some UBERON:0004176|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0002060|UBERON:0001355|UBERON:0013137

name: superficial external pudendal artery
description: An artery that arises from the medial side of the femoral artery, close to the superficial epigastric artery and superficial iliac circumflex artery.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001308|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002060|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0035549|RO:0002178 some UBERON:0004176|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0002060|UBERON:0004573|UBERON:0013137

name: saphenous vein
description: Either of two main superficial veins of the leg, one larger than the other, that begin at the foot.

name: pancreatic lobule
description: A dense accumulation of exocrine glands in the pancreas often surrounding islets of Langerhans.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000017|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0001263|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0014719|UBERON:0000064|UBERON:0004119

name: pancreatic duct
description: A duct that collects and carries secretions of the exocrine pancreas to the intestine.
parents: BFO:0000050 some RO:0002577|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000017|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001264|RO:0002170 some UBERON:0000160|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0003922|RO:0002433 some UBERON:0000017|UBERON:0003928|UBERON:0004119

name: nidopallium
description: The nidopallium, meaning nested pallium, is the region of the avian brain that is used mostly for some types of executive functions but also other higher cognitive tasks.

name: hyperpallium
description: A pallial structure unique to avians.

name: arcopallium
description: A pallial region found in avias that partially overlap regions homologous to the amygdala of mammals.

name: cartilage of pharyngotympanic tube
description: A triangular plate of elastic fibrocartilage that forms the cartilage component of the pharyngotympanic tube.

name: bony part of pharyngotympanic tube
description: The bony part of pharyngotympanic tube is about 12 mm. in length. It begins in the carotid wall of the tympanic cavity, below the septum canalis musculotubarii, and, gradually narrowing, ends at the angle of junction of the squama and the petrous portion of the temporal bone, its extremity presenting a jagged margin which serves for the attachment of the cartilaginous portion.

name: crop
description: A pouched enlargement of the gullet of many birds that serves as a receptacle for food and for its preliminary maceration.

name: proventriculus
description: The glandular or true stomach of a bird that is situated between the crop and gizzard.
parents: BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0010038|RO:0002150 some UBERON:0005052|RO:0002150 some UBERON:0007356|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:8782|RO:0002215 some GO:0001696|UBERON:0011953

name: abomasum
description: The fourth stomach of ruminating animals, which is an elongated pear-shaped sac lying on the floor of the abdomen, on the right-hand side, and roughly between the seventh and twelfth ribs. It leads to the beginning of the small intestine. (Adapted From Black's Veterinary Dictionary, 17th ed).

name: ruminant forestomach
description: Any of the first three stomachs of a ruminant, i.e., the rumen, reticulum, or omasum.

name: ruminant reticulum
description: The second stomach of ruminants. It lies almost in the midline in the front of the abdomen, in contact with the liver and diaphragm and communicates freely with the RUMEN via the ruminoreticular orifice. The lining of the reticulum is raised into folds forming a honeycomb pattern over the surface. (From Concise Veterinary Dictionary, 1988).

name: omasum
description: The third stomach of ruminants, situated on the right side of the abdomen at a higher level than the fourth stomach and between this latter and the second stomach, with both of which it communicates. From its inner surface project large numbers of leaves or folia, each of which possesses roughened surfaces. In the center of each folium is a band of muscle fibers which produces a rasping movement of the leaf when it contracts. One leaf rubs against those on either side of it, and large particles of food material are ground down between the rough surfaces, preparatory to further digestion in the succeeeding parts of the alimentary canal. (Black's Veterinary Dictionary, 17th ed).

name: rumen
description: The first compartment of the ruminant stomach. It lies on the left side of the body, occupying the whole of the left side of the abdomen and even stretching across the median plane of the body to the right side. It is capacious, divided into an upper and a lower sac, each of which has a blind sac at its posterior extremity.

name: ruminant stomach
description: The ruminants' stomach consists of four compartments: rumen, reticulum, omasum and abomasum. The first three compartments comprise the forestomach (proventriculus). They are lined with nonglandular membrane. The fourth compartment, the abomasum comprises the true stomach of the ruminants. It is lined with glandular mucous membrane. The rumen lies on the left of the abdominal cavity, the reticulum cranially and the omasum on the right. The abomasum lies ventrally, its proximal end lies ventral to the rumen, reticulum and omasum.

name: surface of tongue
description: An anatomical surface that is part of a tongue.

name: superior surface of tongue
description: The upper (superior) side of the tongue.

name: inferior surface of tongue
description: The lower (inferior) side of the tongue.

name: incus cartilage element
description: An incus endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: roof of mouth
description: A multi-tissue structure consisting of bone and soft tissue that forms a part of the roof of the oral cavity. In mammals this is the combination of the primary palate (premaxilla) and the secondary palate. In early tetrapods it consists of the vomer, pterygoid, parasphenoid, palatine and ectopterygoid bones.

name: outer epithelium
description: The epidermis is the entire outer epithelial layer of an animal, it may be a single layer that produces an extracellular material (e.g. the cuticle of arthropods) or a complex stratified squamous epithelium, as in the case of many vertebrate species[GO].
parents: RO:0002007 some UBERON:0000468|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:6072|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0007383|UBERON:0003102|UBERON:0010371

name: stratum compactum of dermis
description: Portion of the dermis characterized by a well-arranged, plywood-like, collagenous network.

name: egg yolk
description: The yellow spheroidal mass of stored food that forms the inner portion of the egg of a bird or reptile and is surrounded by the white.

name: shelled egg
description: The hard-shelled reproductive body produced by a bird (especially by the common domestic chicken) or a reptile; also: its contents used as food.

name: dermal scale
description: Dermal bone that is thin, flexible, and platelike, and that develops in overlapping skinfolds that cover the body and often the head of fish and the bases of the fins.

name: enveloping layer of ectoderm
description: Outermost layer of cells surrounding the embryo.

name: appendage lymph vessel
description: A lymphatic vessel that is part of a limb/fin.

name: pectoral appendage lymph vessel
description: A lymphatic vessel that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: paired limb/fin cartilage
description: A cartilage tissue that is part of a paired limb or fin.

name: pectoral appendage cartilage tissue
description: A cartilage tissue that is part of a pectoral appendage.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0004710|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0007272|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|UBERON:0004120|UBERON:0007389

name: pelvic appendage cartilage tissue
description: A cartilage tissue that is part of a pelvic appendage.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0004709|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0007273|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|UBERON:0004120|UBERON:0007389

name: midbrain raphe nuclei
description: Midline nuclei found in the midbrain, includes the dorsal raphe nucleus and the rostral linear nucleus of raphe.

name: nucleus of pontine reticular formation
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a pontine reticular formation.

name: nucleus of midbrain tegmentum
description: A nucleus of brain that spans a midbrain tegmentum.

name: nucleus of midbrain reticular formation
description: A nucleus of midbrain tegmentum that is part of a midbrain reticular formation.

name: cerebellar peduncle
description: Any of the three large paired bundles of nerve fibers that connect the cerebellum to the brain stem.

name: neural decussation
description: Nerve fibers crossing the midline of the neuraxis relative to their point of origin, on a course to from one level of the nervous system to another. (CUMBO, Heimer, L. The Human Brain, 2nd ed., 1995, pg 6).

name: decussation of diencephalon
description: A neural decussation that is part of a diencephalon.

name: stratum intermedium of tooth
description: The stratum intermedium in a developing tooth is a layer of two or three cells between the inner enamel epithelium and the newly forming cells of the stellate reticulum. It first appears during the early bell stage of tooth development, at around the 14th week of intrauterine life (in humans). The stratum intermedium has a notably high alkaline phosphatase activity. This layer, along with the inner enamel epithelium, is responsible for the tooth enamel formation. It is a part of the dental (enamel) organ.

name: lumen of epithelial sac
description: The space within an epithelial sphere.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0007499|RO:0000086 some PATO:0000608|RO:0002572 some UBERON:0007499|UBERON:0012467

name: matrix-based tissue
description: A tissue whose predominant feature is extracellular matrix which may or may not be highly hydrated or calcified.

name: fluid-based anatomical entity
description: Fluid anatomical entity containing cells.

name: keratin-based acellular structure
description: Acellular anatomical structure whose predominant constituent is keratin.

name: chitin-based acellular structure
description: Acellular anatomical structure whose predominant constituent is chitin.

name: epithelial sac
description: An epithelial tube that is open at one end only.

name: epithelial tube open at both ends
description: An epithelial tube open at both ends that allows fluid flow.

name: arborizing epithelial duct system
description: A collection of connected epithelial tubes with a single portal.

name: epithelial plexus
description: A complex of interlinking epithelial tubules.

name: epithelial vesicle
description: A closed epithelium with a lumen.

name: smooth muscle sphincter
description: A ring of smooth muscle cells whose contraction closes the opening of the ring.

name: striated muscle sphincter
description: A ring of striated muscle cells whose contraction closes the opening of the ring.

name: dense mesenchyme tissue
description: Mesenchyme with little extracellular matrix.

name: loose mesenchyme tissue
description: Mesenchyme whose cells are embedded in obvious amounts of extracellular matrix.

name: migrating mesenchyme population
description: Mesenchymal cells that are migrating.

name: regenerating anatomical structure
description: An anatomical structure that is undergoing regeneration.

name: migrating epithelium
description: An epithelium that extends its surface area by peripheral movement.

name: ciliated columnar oviduct epithelium
description: A ciliated columnar epithelium that is part of a oviduct.

name: cuboidal oviduct epithelium
description: A cuboidal epithelium that is part of a oviduct.

name: ciliated columnar epithelium
description: Simple columnar epithelium in which the luminal side of the cells bears cilia. Examples: epithelium of trachea, epithelium of uterine tube.[FMA].

name: stratified columnar epithelium
description: Stratified columnar epithelia is a rare type of epithelial tissue composed of column shaped cells arranged in multiple layers. Stratified columnar epithelia are found in the ocular conjunctiva of the eye, in parts of the pharynx and anus, the female's uterus, the male urethra and vas deferens. Also found in intralobular ducts in salivary glands.[WP].

name: stratified cuboidal epithelium
description: Stratified cuboidal epithelia is a rare type of epithelial tissue composed of cuboidally shaped cells arranged in multiple layers. They protect areas such as ducts of sweat glands, mammary glands, and salivary glands.

name: tibial artery
description: The anterior and posterior arteries created at the bifurcation of the popliteal artery. The anterior tibial artery begins at the lower border of the popliteus muscle and lies along the tibia at the distal part of the leg to surface superficially anterior to the ankle joint. Its branches are distributed throughout the leg, ankle, and pes. The posterior tibial artery begins at the lower border of the popliteus muscle, lies behind the tibia in the lower part of its course, and is found situated between the medial malleolus and the medial process of the calcaneal tuberosity. Its branches are distributed throughout the leg and foot.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002103|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002250|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0002250|UBERON:0001637|UBERON:0003516|UBERON:0004573

name: extensor digitorum communis
description: A muscle on the back of the forearm that extends the fingers and wrist.
parents: RO:0002373 some UBERON:0004300|RO:0002568 some UBERON:0001523|RO:0002568 some UBERON:0003222|UBERON:0011024

name: extensor digiti minimi muscle
description: The extensor minimi digiti (extensor digiti quinti proprius) is a slender muscle of the forearm, placed on the ulnar side of the Extensor digitorum communis, with which it is generally connected. It arises from the common Extensor tendon by a thin tendinous slip, from the intermuscular septa between it and the adjacent muscles. Its tendon runs through a compartment of the dorsal carpal ligament behind the distal radio-ulnar joint, then divides into two as it crosses the manus, and finally joins the expansion of the Extensor digitorum communis tendon on the dorsum of the first phalanx of the little finger[WP].

name: prostate gland ventral lobe
description: Prostate gland lobe that in the mouse has the following characteristics: grossly, clear, gelatinous, and leaf-like; originates ventrally and wraps incompletely around the urethra dorsally, bilaterally. Simple columnar epithelium with the least amount of infolding. Secretory cells are oval and have slightly foamy cytoplasm; nuclei and basal nucleoli are inconspicuous. The secretion is pale and homogeneous. The stroma is thin.

name: layer of synovial tissue
description: A thin, loose vascular connective tissue that makes up the membranes surrounding joints and the sheaths protecting tendons (particularly flexor tendons in the hands and feet) where they pass over bony prominences. Synovial tissue contains synovial cells, which secrete a viscous liquid called synovial fluid; this liquid contains protein and hyaluronic acid and serves as a lubricant and nutrient for the joint cartilage surfaces[BTO]. Synovial tissue can be found in tendons (tissues that connect muscle to bone), bursae (fluid-filled, cushioning sacs found in spaces between tendons, ligaments, and bones), and the cavity (hollow enclosed area) that separates the bones of a freely movable joint, such as the knee or elbow[BTO].

name: synovial cavity of joint
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a synovial joint.

name: synovial cavity of hip joint
description: A synovial cavity of joint that is part of a hip joint.

name: comb and wattle
description: A wattle is a fleshy dewlap or caruncle hanging from various parts of the head or neck in several groups of birds, goats and other animals. In some birds the caruncle is erectile tissue.

name: pigment epithelium of eye
description: Epithelial layer of the retina, ciliary body, or iris composed of cells containing pigment granules.

name: lateral septal complex
description: The lateral septal area; largest nuclear mass in this region, plays a pivotal role in various physiological processes, such as aggression, emotion, thermoregulation, water and food intake and sexual behaviour.

name: medial septal complex
description: A septal nuclear complex that consists of the nucleus of the diagonal bands and the septal medial nuclei.

name: septohippocampal nucleus
description: Part of septal nuclear complex. In the human, it refers to the most caudal of scattered clusters of neurons in the septum pellucidum that extend, on the underside of the corpus callosum, from the level of the medial septal nucleus to the CA fields ( Crosby-1962 ). In the rat it is associated with the lateral septal nucleus throughout its rostro-caudal course toward the CA fields ( Swanson-1998. Adapted from Brain Info.

name: nucleus of trapezoid body
description: A nucleus embedded within the fibers of the trapezoid body.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000988|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002128|RO:0001025 some UBERON:0002932|UBERON:0006331|UBERON:0007247

name: parabrachial nucleus
description: A nucleus of the parabrachial area, which in the human brain is a horseshoe-shaped strip of gray matter comprising the Klliker-Fuse nucleus, the lateral parabrachial nucleus and the medial parabrachial nucleus.

name: nucleus of medulla oblongata
description: A neural nucleus that is part of a medulla oblongata.

name: hippocampus stratum lucidum
description: Layer of hippocampus area CA3 lying superficial to the pyramidal cell layer that contains mossy fiber axons projecting from the dentate gyrus. A slight thickening in this layer marks the border in some species between areas CA2 and CA3. dapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 460).
parents: BFO:0000051 some GO:0097457|BSPO:0001107 some UBERON:0005372|BSPO:0015014 some UBERON:0002313|UBERON:0002305

name: hippocampus alveus
description: Regional part of fornix consisting of a thin layer of white matter on the surface of the hippocampal formation, bordering the wall of the lateral ventricle and composed of white, myelinated fibers. The alveus arises from cell bodies in the subiculum and hippocampus, and eventually merges with the fimbria of the hippocampus. The fimbria goes on to become the fornix (MM: 2006-10-26).

name: hippocampus stratum lacunosum moleculare
description: Layer of the hippocampus lying just superficial to the stratum radiatum and bounded by the pial surface of the hippocampus. The fibers of the perforant pathway fibers from entorhinal cortex and several other brain areas terminate in this layer. Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 460).
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001954|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0005368|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0005370|BSPO:0001101 some UBERON:0001954|BSPO:0015014 some UBERON:0005372|UBERON:0002305

name: trigeminal nuclear complex
description: The sensory trigeminal nerve nuclei are the largest of the cranial nerve nuclei, and extend through the whole of the midbrain, pons and medulla. There is also a distinct trigeminal motor nucleus that is medial to the chief sensory nucleus[WP].
parents: BFO:0000050 some RO:0002577|RO:0002131 some UBERON:0003023|UBERON:0007245|obo:uberon/core#extends_fibers_into some UBERON:0001645

name: ligamentum arteriosum
description: A small ligament attached to the superior surface of the pulmonary trunk and the inferior surface of the aortic arch. It is a nonfunctional vestige of the ductus arteriosus, and is formed within three weeks of birth. The ligamentum arteriosum is closely related to the left recurrent laryngeal nerve, a branch of the left vagus nerve. After splitting from the left vagus nerve, the left recurrent laryngeal loops around the aortic arch posterior to the ligamentum arteriosum, after which it ascends to the larynx[WP].

name: node of ligamentum arteriosum
description: An inconstant lymph node of the anterior mediastinal group located adjacent to the ligamentum arteriosum.

name: thoracic lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of a thorax. Includes lymph nodes of the lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes.

name: future meninx
description: A developing mesenchymal capsule that covers the developing brain and spinal cord and is the precursor of the meningeal cluster. In mammals this gives rise to the arachnoid mater, pia mater and dura mater. In cyclostomes and fishes, the future meninx gives rise to a single meningeal layer, the primitive meninx.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000922|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0010743|RO:0002254 some UBERON:0007213|RO:0002387 some UBERON:0002360|UBERON:0006598

name: ectomeninx
description: The outermost layer of the mesenchymal capsule that surrounds the developing brain, of mixed paraxial mesoderm and neural crest origin. The ectomeninx forms the dura mater (both inner layer and outer chondrogenic layer).
parents: RO:0002202 some UBERON:0009617|RO:0002254 some UBERON:0007213|RO:0002387 some UBERON:0002363|UBERON:0007645

name: esophagogastric junction
description: The junction between the esophagus and the stomach epithelium.

name: anatomical junction
description: An anatomical structure that connects two structures.

name: capillary loop nephron
description: Developing nephron where the developing glomerular capsule has been invaded by a glomerular capillary loop called the glomerular tuft.

name: lateral recess of fourth ventricle
description: The lateral recess is a projection of the fourth ventricle which extends into the inferior cerebellar peduncle of the brainstem. The lateral aperture, an opening in each extremity of the lateral recess, provides a conduit for cerebrospinal fluid to flow from the brain's ventricular system into the subarachnoid space.

name: anular ligament of radius
description: The anular ligament (orbicular ligament) is a strong band of fibers, which encircles the head of the radius (bone), and retains it in contact with the radial notch of the ulna.

name: intersomitic vein
description: The vein that sprouts from the posterior cardinal vein, growing dorsally between the somites, and then joining, and draining the dorsal longitudinal anastomosing vessel.

name: facial neural crest
description: Cranial neural crest that is part of the facial region.

name: uriniferous tubule
description: Functional unit of the kidney that forms urine, consisting of two parts, the nephron and the collecting tubule.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002113|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0001232|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0001285|UBERON:0003914|UBERON:0004819|UBERON:0006555

name: anlage
description: Anlagen are populations of contiguous cells, typically arranged in one plane, that are morphologically indistinct, but that already correspond in extent to a later organ/tissue.

name: gustatory pore
description: The minute opening of a taste bud on the surface of the oral mucosa through which the gustatory hairs of the specialised neuroepithelial gustatory cells project.

name: nucleus of thalamus
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a thalamus.

name: caroticotympanic artery
description: The caroticotympanic branch (tympanic branch) is small; it enters the tympanic cavity through a minute foramen in the carotid canal, and anastomoses with the anterior tympanic branch of the internal maxillary, and with the stylomastoid artery.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001532|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0005608|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0001532|UBERON:0003496|UBERON:0004573|UBERON:0010314

name: tract of spinal cord
description: An axon tract that is part of a spinal cord.

name: tract of brain
description: An axon tract that is part of a brain.

name: spinothalamic tract
description: A tract that originates from neurons in the spinal central gray and projects to various somatosensory nuclei of the thalamus. It is formed in the medulla by merger of the anterior spinothalamic tract and lateral spinothalamic tract (adapted from Braininfo.org).

name: superior cerebellar peduncle of midbrain
description: Regional part of superior cerebellar peduncle, located in the midbrain, consisting of a large bundle of fibers largely projecting from the deep cerebellar nuclei to the midbrain and thalamus. It is continuous with the superior cerebellar peduncle of the pons. (MM).

name: interphalangeal joint of pes
description: The interphalangeal articulations of the foot (articulations of the phalanges) are ginglymoid joints, and each has a plantar and two collateral ligaments. The arrangement of these ligaments is similar to that in the metatarsophalangeal articulations: the Extensor tendons supply the places of dorsal ligaments.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001466|RO:0002176 exactly 2 UBERON:0001449|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0001449|UBERON:0001487|UBERON:0006658

name: interphalangeal joint of manus
description: The interphalangeal articulations of hand are hinge-joints of the phalanges of the hand. There are two sets (except in the thumb): 'proximal interphalangeal joints' (PIP), those between the first (also called proximal) and second (intermediate) phalanges 'distal interphalangeal joints' (DIP), those between the second and third (distal) phalanges A similar group of articulations also function in the toes.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002389|RO:0002176 exactly 2 UBERON:0001436|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0001436|UBERON:0001489|UBERON:0006658

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 1
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 1.

name: interphalangeal joint of pedal digit 1
description: An interphalangeal joint of pes that is part of a pedal digit 1.

name: interphalangeal joint of pedal digit 2
description: An interphalangeal joint of pes that is part of a pedal digit 2.

name: interphalangeal joint of pedal digit 3
description: An interphalangeal joint of pes that is part of a pedal digit 3.

name: interphalangeal joint of pedal digit 4
description: An interphalangeal joint of pes that is part of a pedal digit 4.

name: interphalangeal joint of pedal digit 5
description: An interphalangeal joint of pes that is part of a pedal digit 5.

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 2
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 2.

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 3
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 3.

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 4
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 4.

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 5
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 5.

name: metacarpophalangeal joint of manual digit 1
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 1.

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 2.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0003622|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0002374|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0004328|UBERON:0003695

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 3.

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 4.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0003624|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0002374|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0004330|UBERON:0003695

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 5.

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 1.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0003631|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0001448|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0004315|UBERON:0003696

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 2.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0003632|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0001448|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0004316|UBERON:0003696

name: metatarsophalangeal joint of pedal digit 3
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 3.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0003633|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0001448|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0004317|UBERON:0003696

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 4.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0003634|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0001448|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0004318|UBERON:0003696

description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 5.

name: cerebellum vermis culmen
description: The culmen is the portion of the anterior vermis adjacent to the primary fissure of cerebellum. The culmen and the anterior parts of the quadrangular lobules form the lobus culminis[WP].

name: paramedian reticular nucleus
description: A medullary nucleus that sends its connections to the spinal cord in a mostly ipsilateral manner.

name: osphradium
description: The osphradium is the olfactory organ in certain molluscs, linked with the respiration organ. The main function of this is to test incoming water for silt and other possible food particles. It is used by all members of the Genus Conus.

name: epidermis gland
description: A gland that is part of a epidermis.

name: scrotal sweat
description: Any portion of sweat that is produced by a sweat gland of the scrotum.

name: scrotal sweat gland
description: Any sweat gland that is part of a scrotum.

name: secondary dentition
description: The teeth of adulthood that either replace or are added to the complement of deciduous teeth. (Boucher's Clinical Dental Terminology, 4th ed).

name: secondary tooth
description: A tooth that forms after a primary tooth.

name: unerupted tooth
description: A normal developing tooth which has not yet perforated the oral mucosa or one that fails to erupt in the normal sequence or time interval expected for the type of tooth in a given gender, age, or population group.

name: umbilical vein endothelium
description: An endothelium that is part of a umbilical vein.

name: umbilical artery endothelium
description: An endothelium that is part of a umbilical artery.

name: transudate
description: Any bodily fluid that has passed through a membrane such as the capillary wall, as a result of unbalanced hydrostatic and osmotic forces.
parents: CARO:0000000|RO:0000086 some PATO:0001548|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0001969|RO:0002494 some UBERON:0001969|UBERON:0006314|obo:uberon/core#filtered_through some UBERON:0001982

name: exudate
description: Fluids that is discharged from blood vessels usually arising from inflammation or injury.
parents: RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|RO:0002353 some GO:0006954|UBERON:0000463|obo:uberon/core#filtered_through some UBERON:0001981

name: ascitic fluid
description: The serous fluid which accumulates in the peritoneal cavity in ascites.

name: vascular system
description: Anatomical system that consists of all blood and lymph vessels.

name: mixed dentition
description: The complement of teeth in the jaws after the eruption of some of the permanent teeth but before all the deciduous teeth are absent. (Boucher's Clinical Dental Terminology, 4th ed).

name: uropygial gland
description: A large gland at the base of a bird's tail dorsal to the cloaca at the end of the pygostyle that secretes an oil used in preening. It opens through a caudally directed nipple.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002415|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:8782|RO:0002216 some GO:0007625|RO:0002216 some NBO:0000451|RO:0003000 some UBERON:0007803|UBERON:0002365

name: synsacrum
description: A region of the lower vertebral column formed from the fusion of vertebrae.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001130|RO:0002131 some UBERON:0006075|RO:0002374 some UBERON:0002412|UBERON:0001474

name: connecting stalk
description: A bridge of mesoderm connecting the caudal end of the young embryo with the trophoblastic tissues; the precursor of the umbilical cord.

name: connecting stalk vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a connecting stalk.

name: adipose tissue of abdominal region
description: Adipose tissue that is located in the abdominal region. This includes any subcutaneous fat, visceral fat or encapsulated adipose tissue depots.

name: fascia of Camper
description: The superficial layer (fascia of Camper) is a thick superficial layer of the anterior abdominal wall. It is areolar in texture, and contains in its meshes a varying quantity of adipose tissue. It is found superficial to Scarpa's fascia.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0006635|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0013488|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0001013|UBERON:0004120|UBERON:0013493

name: craniocervical region
description: The anteriormost subdivision of the body that includes the head, jaws, pharyngeal region and the neck (if present). In vertebrates this is the subdivision that includes the cervical vertebrae.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000153|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0013702|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0000033|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0006562|CARO:0000000|UBERON:0000475

name: post-anal tail
description: A tail that extends from the posterior tip of the organism to the anus, contains muscle and skeleton.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0006071|CARO:0000000|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7711|RO:0002162 some (not (NCBITaxon:314295))|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0007144|RO:0002216 some GO:0007626|RO:0002494 some UBERON:0007144|UBERON:0002415

name: major alar cartilage
description: The greater alar cartilage (lower lateral cartilage) is a thin, flexible plate, situated immediately below the preceding, and bent upon itself in such a manner as to form the medial wall and lateral wall of the naris of its own side. The portion which forms the medial wall (crus mediale) is loosely connected with the corresponding portion of the opposite cartilage, the two forming, together with the thickened integument and subjacent tissue, the septum mobile nasi. The part which forms the lateral wall (crus laterale) is curved to correspond with the ala of the nose; it is oval and flattened, narrow behind, where it is connected with the frontal process of the maxilla by a tough fibrous membrane, in which are found three or four small cartilaginous plates, the lesser alar cartilages (cartilagines alares minores; sesamoid cartilages). Above, it is connected by fibrous tissue to the lateral cartilage and front part of the cartilage of the septum; below, it falls short of the margin of the naris, the ala being completed by fatty and fibrous tissue covered by skin. In front, the greater alar cartilages are separated by a notch which corresponds with the apex of the nose.

name: minor alar cartilage
description: The part which forms the lateral wall is curved to correspond with the ala of the nose; it is oval and flattened, narrow behind, where it is connected with the frontal process of the maxilla by a tough fibrous membrane, in which are found three or four small cartilaginous plates, the lesser alar cartilages.

name: accessory nasal cartilage
description: Small cartilages of the nose connecting the greater alar cartilage and lateral nasal cartilage.

name: lateral nasal cartilage
description: The lateral cartilage (upper lateral cartilage) is situated below the inferior margin of the nasal bone, and is flattened, and triangular in shape.[WP].

name: vomeronasal cartilage
description: The vomeronasal cartilage (or Jacobson's cartilage) is a narrow strip of cartilage, low on the medial wall of the nasal cavity. It lies between the cartilaginous nasal septum and the vomer. The cartilage lies below, but is not connected to, the rudimentary vomeronasal organ of Jacobson[WP].

name: appendage girdle region
description: An organism subdivision that encompasses the region containing the pectoral or pelvic girdle. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc).
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0010707|CARO:0000003|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:7742|RO:0002551 some UBERON:0010719|UBERON:0000475

name: reticular membrane of spiral organ
description: A reticular lamina of epithelium that is part of a spiral organ of cochlea.

name: peritoneal mesentery
description: Mesentery that is located in the peritoneum.

name: external nose

name: pectoral girdle bone
description: A bone that is part of a pectoral girdle region.

name: pelvic girdle bone/zone
description: A bone element or fused bone that is part of pelvic girdle.

name: pectoral girdle skeleton
description: A subdivision of a limb or fin skeleton consisting of bones which connects the upper limb or fin to the axial skeleton on each side. It consists of the clavicle and scapula in humans and, in those species with three bones in the pectoral girdle, the coracoid. Some mammalian species (e.g. the dog and the horse) have only the scapula. In humans, the only joints between the shoulder girdle and axial skeleton are the sternoclavicular joints on each side. No joint exists between each scapula and the rib cage; instead the muscular connection between the two permits relatively great mobility of the shoulder girdle in relation to the pelvic girdle. In those species having only the scapula, no joint exists between the forelimb and the thorax, the only attachment being muscular[WP]. Examples: There are only two instances, right and left pectoral girdle skeletons.

name: pelvic girdle skeleton
description: Skeletal subdivision consisting of a set of bones linking the axial series to the hindlimb zeugopodium and offering anchoring areas for hindlimb and caudal musculature.

description: Skeletal element that is composed of cartilage tissue and may be permanent or transient.

name: regular connective tissue
description: Connective tissue, which consists of fibroblasts, the intercellular matrix of which contains a regular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: bone (tissue), cartilage (tissue), dense regular connective tissue.

name: dense regular connective tissue
description: Connective tissue that is dominated by collagen fibres organized into a definitive pattern (e.g., parallel to one another), with comparatively fewer cells (mostly fibroblasts).

name: perichordal tissue
description: Fibrous connective tissue that surrounds the notochord; includes a layer of elastin.

description: A bone that is part of a craniocervical region.

name: central carpal bone
description: A small bone occasionally found at the dorsal aspect of the wrist between the scaphoid, capitate, and trapezoid; it is developed as an independent cartilage in early foetal life but usually becomes fused with the scaphoid; it occurs normally in most monkeys.

name: scapholunate
description: The combined scaphoid and lunate bones.

name: sesamoid bone of manus
description: A sesamoid bone that is part of a manus.

name: sesamoid bone of pes
description: A sesamoid bone that is part of a pes.

name: irregular bone
description: The irregular bones are bones which, from their peculiar form, cannot be grouped as long bone, short bone, flat bone or sesamoid bone. Irregular bones serve various purposes in the body, such as protection of nervous tissue, affording multiple anchor points for skeletal muscle attachment (as with the sacrum), and maintaining pharynx and trachea support, and tongue attachment (such as the hyoid bone). They consist of cancellous tissue enclosed within a thin layer of compact bone. The irregular bones are: the vertebrC&, sacrum, coccyx, temporal, sphenoid, ethmoid, zygomatic, maxilla, mandible, palatine, inferior nasal concha, and hyoid.

name: joint of girdle
description: A skeletal joint that is part of a appendage girdle region.

description: A subdivision of the face that is the anteriormost part of the lower jaw region.

name: forehead
description: The part of the face above the eyes[MESH]. In human anatomy, the forehead is the fore part of the head. It is, formally, an area of the head bounded by three features, two of the skull and one of the scalp. The top of the forehead is marked by the hairline, the edge of the area where hair on the scalp grows. The bottom of the forehead is marked by the supraorbital ridge, the bone feature of the skull above the eyes. The two sides of the forehead are marked by the temporal ridge, a bone feature that links the supraorbital ridge to the coronal suture line and beyond[WP].

name: pelvic cavity
description: The part of the ventral body cavity that is within the pelvis.

description: Musculature system of the pharyngeal and head regions.

name: tibialis
description: Either of two muscles of the calf of the leg.

name: dorsal thoracic segment of trunk
description: Subdivision of thorax, which in humans is the posterior part of the thorax and is demarcated from the chest by the external surface of the posterolateral part of the rib cage and the anterior surface of the thoracic vertebral column; together with the chest, it constitutes the thorax.

name: lower back muscle
description: A muscle of back that is part of a lower back.

name: upper back muscle
description: A muscle of back that is part of a dorsal thoracic segment of trunk.

name: pennate muscle
description: A pennate muscle (also called a penniform muscle) is a muscle with fascicles that attach obliquely (in a slanting position) to its tendon. These types of muscles generally allow better stabilization and force production but less flexibility. Individual muscle fibers are formed into bundles of fasciculi and these bundles of fasciculi are formed into bundles of fascicles which compose the entire muscle itself. In a pennate muscle, the fascicles will form an angle with its central tendon. If all the fascicles are on the same side of the tendon, the pennate muscle is called unipennate. Examples of this include certain muscles in the manus. If there are fascicles on both sides of the central tendon, the pennate muscle is called bipennate. The rectus femoris, a large muscle in the quadriceps, is typical. If the central tendon branches within a pennate muscle, the muscle is called multipennate, as seen in the deltoid muscle in the shoulder.

name: pyloric stomach
description: The mouth of a starfish is located on the underside of the body, and opens through a short esophagus into firstly a cardiac stomach, and then, a second, pyloric stomach. Each arm also contains two pyloric caeca, long hollow tubes branching outwards from the pyloric stomach. Each pyloric caecum is lined by a series of digestive glands, which secrete digestive enzymes and absorb nutrients from the food. A short intestine runs from the upper surface of the pyloric stomach to open at an anus in the center of the upper body.

name: tube foot
description: One of the numerous external, fluid-filled muscular tubes of echinoderms, such as the starfish or sea urchin, serving as organs of locomotion, food handling, and respiration[BTO]. Tube feet consist of two parts: ampulla and podia. Ampulla contain both circular muscles and longitudinal muscle, whereas the podia contain the latter only. Thus the podia use suction to attach to the substratum[WP].

name: echinoderm pyloric cecum
description: The pyloric ceca (or digestive glands) and the cardiac stomach produce digestive enzymes in starfishes. Digested material is absorbed through the pyloric ceca for transport to the rest of the body. Each pyloric cecum extends the length of each arm.

name: cardiac stomach
description: In starfishes the cardiac stomach is connected to a pyloric stomach which is located above it. Food can be brought into the stomach through the mouth or, in many species, the cardiac stomach can be extended out through the mouth to digest food outside the body. Suspension-feeding starfish use their tube feet to pass food to the mouth.

name: water vascular system
description: The water vascular system is a hydraulic system used by echinoderms, such as sea stars and sea urchins, for locomotion, food and waste transportation, and respiration. The system is composed of canals connecting numerous tube feet. Echinoderms move by alternately contracting muscles that force water into the tube feet, causing them to extend and push against the ground, then relaxing to allow the feet to retract.

name: Aristotle's lantern
description: Within the mouth of a sea urchin is an elaborate five-sided jaw structure called Aristotles lantern that can be partially extruded from the mouth. It is able to grind up calcareous exoskeletons of plants and animals.

description: A clavicle that is in the right side of a entire appendicular skeleton.

name: left clavicle
description: A clavicle that is in the left side of a entire appendicular skeleton.

name: periodontal ligament
description: The fibrous connective tissue that surrounds the root of a tooth, separating it from and attaching it to the alveolar bone. It extends from the base of the gingival mucosa to the fundus of the bony socket, and its main function is to hold the tooth in its socket[BTO].
