name: cavity of right ventricle
description: Luminal space of the right ventricle of the heart.

name: epithelium of male urethra
description: An epithelium that is part of a male urethra.

name: lamina propria of fundus of stomach
description: A lamina propria that is part of a mucosa of fundus of stomach.

name: lumen of duodenum
description: An anatomical space that is part of a duodenum.

name: cavity of left atrium
description: Luminal space of the left atrium of the heart.

name: cavity of left ventricle
description: Luminal space of the left ventricle of the heart.

name: muscular layer of prostatic urethra
description: A muscular coat that is part of a prostatic urethra.

name: lamina propria of prostatic urethra
description: A lamina propria that is part of a prostatic urethra.

name: lumen of jejunum
description: An anatomical space that is part of a jejunum.

name: muscularis mucosae of jejunum
description: A muscularis mucosa that is part of a jejunum.

name: epithelium of female urethra
description: An epithelium that is part of a female urethra.

name: cavity of right atrium
description: Luminal space of the right atrium of the heart.

name: muscle layer of spongiose part of urethra
description: A muscular coat that is part of a spongiose part of urethra.

name: frontal lobe
description: Frontal lobe is the anterior-most of five lobes of the cerebral hemisphere. It is bounded by the central sulcus on its posterior border and by the longitudinal cerebral fissure on its medial border.
parents: RO:0002220 some UBERON:0001871|RO:0002220 some UBERON:0001872|RO:0002433 some UBERON:0001893|UBERON:0016526

name: lobe of cerebral hemisphere
description: Subdivision of telencephalon which is one of a number of subdivisions of each hemisphere separated by both real landmarks (sulci and fissures) and arbitrary boundaries[FMA,modified].

name: white matter of frontal lobe
description: A white matter of cerebral lobe that is part of a frontal lobe.

name: cortex of cerebral lobe
description: Grey matter neocortex region of a lobe of the cerebral hemisphere.

name: parietal cortex
description: Gray matter of the parietal region of the neocortex, located in the parietal lobe of gyrencephalic animals. It is continuous anteriorly with the frontal cortex, posteriorly with the occipital cortex and medially with the insular cortex and with the temporal cortex on the posterior/inferior border.

name: white matter of parietal lobe
description: A white matter of cerebral lobe that is part of a parietal lobe.

name: white matter of temporal lobe
description: A white matter of cerebral lobe that is part of a temporal lobe.

name: white matter of occipital lobe
description: A white matter of cerebral lobe that is part of a occipital lobe.

name: white matter of limbic lobe
description: A white matter of cerebral lobe that is part of a limbic lobe.

name: temporal cortex
description: Gray matter of the temporal region of the neocortex, located in the temporal lobe in gyrencephalic animals.

name: pharyngeal ectoderm
description: The external part of the developing pharynx that is made of ectoderm. During vertebrate development, pockets form in pharyngeal ectoderm between the pharyngeal arches.

name: central nervous system gray matter layer
description: A layer of of the central nervous system that is part of gray matter.

name: central nervous system white matter layer
description: A layer of of the central nervous system that is composed of white matter.

name: phlegm
description: Mucus produced in the respiratory tract.

name: white matter of midbrain
description: A white matter that is part of the midbrain.

name: stria of telencephalon
description: A stria of neuraxis that is part of a telencephalon.

name: superficial cerebral vein
description: The superficial cerebral veins are a group of veins in the head. This group includes the superior cerebral veins.

name: deep cerebral vein
description: The deep cerebral veins are a group of veins in the head. This group includes the superior thalamostriate vein.

name: pit
description: An roughly circular indentation in a surface.

name: statoconial membrane
description: An acellular membrane in the vestibular labyrinth that is composed of the otoconial layer, gelatinous layer, and a subcupular meshwork.

name: lamina V of gray matter of spinal cord
description: Spinal lamina V is a lamina of the spinal cord. It is also known as the neck of the posterior horn.

name: lamina VI of gray matter of spinal cord
description: Spinal lamina VI is a lamina of the spinal cord. It is also known as the base of the posterior horn.

name: nucleus proprius of spinal cord
description: The Nucleus proprius is a layer of the spinal cord adjacent to the substantia gelatinosa. Nucleus proprius constitutes the bulk of the dorsal horn and receives inputs from the dorsal root ganglions that carry sensory information, such as light touch, as well as pain and temperature information. Cells in this nucleus project to deeper laminae of the spinal cord, to the posterior column nuclei, and to other supraspinal relay centers including the midbrain, thalamus, and hypothalamus. Rexed laminae III, IV, and V make up the nucleus propius Nucleus proprius (NP), along with nucleus dorsalis (ND) are involved in sensing fine touch and proprioception.

name: neurovascular bundle
description: A body structure consisting of nerves traveling together with arteries, veins, and/or lymphatics.

name: actinopterygian frontal-parietal joint
description: Fibrous joint connecting the actinopterygian frontal bone to the actinopterygian parietal bone.

name: parvocellular reticular nucleus
description: The parvocellular reticular nucleus is part of the brain located dorsolateral to the nucleus reticularis pontis caudalis. The dorsal portion of the reticular nucleus has been shown to innervate the mesencephalic trigeminal nucleus and its surrounding area. Also, it projects to the facial nucleus, hypoglossal nucleus and parabrachial nucleus along with parts of the caudal parvocellular reticular formation. This nucleus is also involved in expiration with a part of the gigantocellular nucleus.

name: premotor cortex
description: The premotor cortex is an area of motor cortex lying within the frontal lobe of the brain. It extends 3 mm anterior to the primary motor cortex, near the Sylvian fissure, before narrowing to approximately 1 mm near the medial longitudinal fissure, which serves as the posterior border for the prefrontal cortex. The premotor cortex is largely equivalent to Brodmann area 6. Activity within this region is critical to the sensory guidance of movement and control of proximal and trunk muscles of the body.

name: supplemental motor cortex
description: The supplementary motor area (SMA) is a part of the sensorimotor cerebral cortex (perirolandic, i.e. on each side of the Rolando or central sulcus). It was included, on purely cytoarchitectonic arguments, in area 6 of Brodmann and the Vogts. It is located on the medial face of the hemisphere, just in front of primary motor cortex. This is an element that appeared late in evolution, in monkeys, linked to the appearance of a true medial pallidum.

name: lateral periolivary nucleus
description: Lateral component of the periolivary nucleus.

name: subparafascicular nucleus
description: The term subparafascicular nucleus refers to a cell group located ventral to the parafascicular nucleus in the thalamus. Identified by internal structure, it is present in the human ( Mai-1997 ), the macaque ( Paxinos-2009a ), the rat ( Swanson-1998 ), and the mouse ( Hof-2000 ).

name: dorsal paramedian reticular nucleus
description: Small nucleus in the brainstem of human, located adjacent and medial to the nucleus prepositus in the dorsal medulla, described in several atlases of human brain stem. In transverse sections, it is oval with its long axis aligned with the dorsal border of the brainstem. It begins at about the same A-P level as the nucleus prepositus, just rostral to the hypoglossal nucleus. It includes calretinin immunoreactive large cells with oval or polygonal cell bodies. Cells are not immunoreactive for either calbindin or parvalbumin, but a few fibers immunoreactive to each protein are found within its central region. Cells in PMD are also immunoreactive to nNOS, and immunoreactivity to a neurofilament protein shows many labeled cells and fibers. According to Baizer et al., no equivalent structure was observed in the cat, rat, mouse or monkey atlas although they did not look at the brains of the great apes.

name: paratrigeminal nucleus
description: The term paratrigeminal nucleus refers to a group of cells located lateral to the spinal trigeminal tract of the medulla and medial to the spinocerebellar tracts at the level of the spinal trigeminal nucleus. The cells, identified by Nissl stain, are partially embedded in the adjacent tracts; their distribution varies by species. The paratrigeminal nucleus may represent an extension of the lateral cervical nucleus into the medulla ( Swanson-2004 ). It is found in the human ( Carpenter-1983 ), the macaque ( Paxinos-2009a ), the rat ( Swanson-2004 ) and the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ). In the functional model of central nervous system organization it is classified as part of the subcortical somatosensory system ( Swanson-2004 ).

name: lateral nucleus of trapezoid body
description: One of two potential parts of the trapezoid nucleus. Separated by an indistinct boundary, the other is the medial trapezoid nucleus ( Crosby-1962 ). The existence of the trapezoid nucleus in the human is disputed ( Bazwinsky-2003 ).
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002128|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002932|BSPO:0000102 some UBERON:0002779|UBERON:0007247

name: retroambiguus nucleus
description: The term retroambiguus nucleus refers to a group of neurons in the medulla at the caudal end of the nucleus ambiguus, from which the cranial part of the accessory nerve originates ( Crosby-1962 ).

name: nucleus of phrenic nerve
description: Neuron cell bodies located in the more medial portions of the anterior horn at cervical levels C3-C7 that innervate the diaphragm via the phrenic nerve.

name: renal fascia
description: A fascial pouch derived from extraperitoneal connective tissue that contains the kidneys, the suprarenal glands, the renal vessels and perirenal fat.

name: future nervous system
description: Primordium that develops into the nervous system.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000922|RO:0002387 some UBERON:0001016|RO:0002496 some UBERON:0000111|UBERON:0006598

name: craniopharyngeal canal
description: The craniopharyngeal canal, is an anatomical feature sometimes found in the sphenoid bone opening to the sella turcica. It is a canal (a passage or channel) sometimes found extending from the anterior part of the fossa hypophyseos of the sphenoid bone to the under surface of the skull, and marks the original position of Rathke's pouch; while at the junction of the septum of the nose with the palate traces of the stomodeal end are occasionally present.

name: ovarian fossa
description: A shallow depression on the lateral wall of the pelvis, wherein the ovary lies. This fossa has the following boundaries: superiorly: by the external iliac vessels anteriorly and inferiorly: by the broad ligament of the uterus posteriorly: by the ureter and internal iliac vessels.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002355|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0005449|RO:0001019 some UBERON:0000992|UBERON:0000464

name: shoulder joint
description: The joint that is formed by the union of the humerus, the scapula (or shoulder blade), and the clavicle (or collarbone). Commonly thought of as a single joint, the shoulder is actually made up of two separate joints - the glenohumeral and acromioclavicular joints.

name: epithelium of terminal part of digestive tract
description: Epithelium lining the distalmost portion of the digestive tract.

name: entire extraembryonic component
description: The part of the conceptus that may be lost before birth or will be discarded at birth, or when the embryo becomes an independent organism.

name: transitional anatomical structure
description: An embryonic anatomical entity that will turn into one or more other anatomical entities, perhaps with other anatomical entities, later in development.

name: periosteum of long bone
description: A periosteum that is part of a long bone.

name: frenulum of upper lip
description: A frenulum of lip that is part of a upper lip.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001834|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0005031|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0005031|UBERON:0005031|UBERON:0016910

name: frenulum of lower lip
description: A frenulum of lip that is part of a lower lip.

name: vermilion
description: The zone of the skin that surrounds a lip and is colored red due to thin epithelium and presence of eleidin.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0000165|RO:0000086 some PATO:0000322|RO:0002221 some UBERON:0001833|UBERON:0001084

name: upper vermilion
description: A vermilion that is part of a upper lip.

name: lower vermilion
description: A vermilion that is part of a lower lip.

name: preductal region of aortic arch
description: Area of aorta proximal to the ductus arteriosus.

name: postductal region of aortic arch
description: Area of aorta distal to the ductus arteriosus.

name: juxtaductal region of aortic arch
description: Area of aorta at the area of insertion to the ductus arteriosus.

name: mucus body coating
description: A coating of mucus that is produced by the skin and covers all or most of the body of an animal.

name: metaphysis of fibula
description: A metaphysis that is part of a fibula.

name: lingual cusp of tooth
description: A medially (towards the tongue)) raised feature found on crown of a tooth.

name: transverse ridge of tooth
description: Triangular ridges facing each other and crossing at transverse angle, forming a transverse ridge on posterior teeth.

name: incisive process of premaxilla
description: A small protuberence on the lingual surface of the premaxilla, immediately posterior to the teeth.

name: cingulum of tooth
description: The portion of the teeth, occurring on the lingual or palatal aspects, that forms a convex protuberance at the cervical third of the anatomic crown. It represents the lingual or palatal developmental lobe of these teeth.

name: vomerine dentition
description: A set of teeth in which each tooth that attaches to a vomer.

name: extensor pollicis brevis muscle
description: The Extensor pollicis brevis lies on the medial side of, and is closely connected with, the Abductor pollicis longus.

name: transverse folds of rectum
description: Houston's valves (or transverse folds of rectum) are semi-lunar transverse folds of the rectal wall that protrude into the anal canal. Their use seems to be to support the weight of fecal matter, and prevent its urging toward the anus, which would produce a strong urge to defecate. Although the term rectum means straight, these transverse folds overlap each other during the empty state of the intestine to such an extent that, as Houston remarked, they require considerable maneuvering to conduct an instrument along the canal, as often occurs in sigmoidoscopy and colonoscopy. These folds are about 12 mm. in width and are composed of the circular muscle coat of the rectum. They are usually three in number; sometimes a fourth is found, and occasionally only two are present. One is situated near the commencement of the rectum, on the right side. A second extends inward from the left side of the tube, opposite the middle of the sacrum. A third, the largest and most constant, projects backward from the forepart of the rectum, opposite the fundus of the urinary bladder. When a fourth is present, it is situated nearly 2.5 cm above the anus on the left and posterior wall of the tube.

name: marginal venous sinus
description: A paired dural venous sinus at the rim of the foramen magnum.

name: primitive marginal sinus
description: The primitive marginal sinuses (PMS) are embryonic sinuses forming the later superior sagittal sinus.

name: meningeal branch of spinal nerve
description: Branch of spinal nerve that innervates the structures of the vertebral column.

name: communicating branch of spinal nerve
description: Rami communicans (plural rami communicantes) is the term used for a nerve which connects two other nerves. When used without further definition, it almost always refers to a communicating branch between a spinal nerve and the sympathetic trunk. More specifically, it usually refers to one of the following: Gray ramus communicans White ramus communicans.

name: external thoracic vein
description: Extension of the long thoracic vein that collects blood from the mammary glands.

name: internal mammary vein
description: One of two veins running parallel to their corresponding internal mammary arteries that unite forming one vessel. These veins drain the chest wall into the innominate vein.

name: prevertebral muscle of neck
description: A prevertebral muscle that is part of a neck.

name: ventral body wall
description: The ventral part of the body wall.

name: developing mesenchymal structure
description: A mesenchyme-derived anatomical entity undergoing a transtion to become another structure.

name: buccal gland
description: Any of the small racemose mucous glands in the mucous membrane lining the cheeks.

name: bony part of cervical vertebral arch
description: A bony part of vertebral arch that is part of a cervical vertebral arch.

name: bony part of vertebral arch of first sacral vertebra
description: A bony part of vertebral arch that is part of a sacral vertebra 1.

name: abdominal viscera
description: A viscus that is part of a abdomen.

name: internal surface of cranial base
description: Internal (endosteal) surface of the base of skull.

name: thenar eminence
description: A raised fleshy area on the palm of the hand near the base of the thumb.

name: hypothenar eminence
description: Hypothenar refers to a group of three muscles of the palm that control the motion of the little finger. The three muscles are: Abductor digiti minimi Flexor digiti minimi Opponens digiti minimi.

name: raphe of scrotum
description: A ridge of tissue that extends along the midline of the scrotum.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001300|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0035106|BSPO:0005001 some UBERON:0001300|RO:0000086 some PATO:0002358|RO:0002150 some UBERON:0006655|RO:0002202 some UBERON:0013241|UBERON:0004120|UBERON:0005156|UBERON:0034929

name: lower primary incisor tooth
description: A primary incisor tooth that is part of a lower jaw region.

name: posterior fascicle of palatopharyngeus
description: The thinner portion of the muscle of the palatopharyngeal arch, originating in the region of the midline where its fibers interdigitate with the contralateral partner, then passing posterior to the levator veli palatini muscle to join the longitudinal layer of pharyngeal musculature; acts as a sort of sphincter, reducing the caliber of the isthmus of fauces at the palatopharyngeal arch.

name: superior auricular muscle
description: The superior auricular muscle, the largest of the three auriculares muscles, is also thin and fan-shaped. Its fibers arise from the galea aponeurotica, and converge to be inserted by a thin, flattened tendon into the upper part of the cranial surface of the auricula.

name: anterior auricular muscle
description: The anterior auricular muscle, the smallest of the three auriculares muscles, is thin and fan-shaped, and its fibers are pale and indistinct. It arises from the lateral edge of the galea aponeurotica, and its fibers converge to be inserted into a projection on the front of the helix.

name: posterior auricular muscle
description: The posterior auricular muscle consists of two or three fleshy fasciculi, which arise from the mastoid portion of the temporal bone by short aponeurotic fibers. They are inserted into the lower part of the cranial surface of the concha.

name: muscle layer of rectum
description: A muscle layer that is part of the rectum.

name: left kidney interstitium
description: A kidney interstitium that is part of a left kidney.

name: right kidney interstitium
description: A kidney interstitium that is part of a right kidney.

name: left renal pelvis
description: A renal pelvis that is part of a left ureter.

name: right renal pelvis
description: A renal pelvis that is part of a right ureter.

name: periovarian fat pad
description: The encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the ovaries.

name: mammary lobe
description: A cluster of mammary gland lobules. In humans this is a distinct lobe and located in the breast region.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001911|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002100|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0001912|UBERON:0004121|UBERON:0009912

name: anterior perforated substance
description: Regional part of telencephalon lying on the basal surface and bounded by the olfactory trigone rostrally, the diagonal band medially and caudally and the prepiriform cortex laterally. It is characterized by many perforations caused by small blood vessels entering the gray matter (Meyer et al., J. Comp. Neurol 284: 405, 1989).

name: transverse process of cervical vertebra
description: A transverse process that is part of a cervical vertebra.

name: cervical rib
description: A rib that is attached to a cervical vertebra.

name: transverse process of lumbar vertebra
description: A transverse process that is part of a lumbar vertebra.

name: angle of oral opening
description: The lateral limit of each lateral part of the oral fissure.

name: skin of lower lip
description: A zone of skin that is part of a lower lip.

name: skin of upper lip
description: A zone of skin that is part of a upper lip.

name: pars flaccida of tympanic membrane
description: A small, triangular, flaccid portion of the tympanic membrane, or eardrum, lying above the malleolar folds, attached directly to the petrous bone at the notch of Rivinus.

name: annular ligament of stapes
description: A ring of fibrous tissue that connects the base of the stapes to the oval window of the inner ear.

name: pulmonary part of lymphatic system
description: An organ system subdivision that is the part of the lymphoid system that includes the pulmonary lymphatic vessels.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002048|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0006558|BFO:0000051 some UBERON:0018227|UBERON:0004119|UBERON:0011216

name: pulmonary lymphatic vessel
description: A lymphatic vessel that is part of a lung.

name: renin-angiotensin system
description: A system consisting of renin, angiotensin-converting enzyme, and angiotensin II. Renin, an enzyme produced in the kidney, acts on angiotensinogen, an alpha-2 globulin produced by the liver, forming angiotensin I. The converting enzyme contained in the lung acts on angiotensin I in the plasma converting it to angiotensin II, the most powerful directly pressor substance known. It causes contraction of the arteriolar smooth muscle and has other indirect actions mediated through the adrenal cortex.

name: femoral canal
description: The compartment of the femoral sheath that contains efferent lymphatic vessels and a lymph node embedded in a small amount of areolar tissue. It is conical in shape and is about 2 cm long. The femoral canal is bordered: Anteriorly by the inguinal ligament Posteriorly by the pectineal ligament Medially by the lacunar ligament Laterally by the femoral vein It contains the lymph nodes of Cloquet or Rosenmuller. It should not be confused with the nearby adductor canal.

name: labyrinthine artery
description: A long slender branch of the anterior inferior cerebellar artery (85%-100% cases) or basilar artery (<15% cases), arises from near the middle of the artery; it accompanies the vestibulocochlear nerve through the internal acoustic meatus, and is distributed to the internal ear.
parents: BFO:0000050 some RO:0002577|BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001846|RO:0002170 some UBERON:0009689|UBERON:0001637|UBERON:0003496|UBERON:0004121|UBERON:0010314

name: gland of Zeis
description: Glands of Zeis are unilobar sebaceous glands located on the margin of the eyelid. The glands of Zeis service the eyelash. These glands produce an oily substance that is issued through the excretory ducts of the sebaceous lobule into the middle portion of the hair follicle.

name: stroma of pancreas
description: A stroma that is part of a pancreas.

name: dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway
description: A sensory tract originating in the spinal cord responsible for transmitting fine touch, vibration and conscious proprioceptive information from the body to the cerebral cortex. The components include the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus.

name: dorsal column nucleus
description: A nucleus that contain secondary neurons of the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway, which carries fine touch and proprioceptive information from the body to the brain. Examples: gracile nucleus, cuneat nucleus, nucleus of Bishoff.

name: panniculus carnosus muscle
description: The skeletal muscle layer in the superficial fascia deep to the panniculus adiposus.
parents: BSPO:0000107 some UBERON:0013488|RO:0002005 some UBERON:0001780|RO:0002160 some NCBITaxon:40674|RO:0002162 some (not (NCBITaxon:9606))|UBERON:0008876

name: palatine bone horizontal plate
description: The part of the palatine bone that forms the posterior part (approximately one third) of the bony palate.(Stedmans).

name: thymic artery
description: A vein that supplies blood to the thymus.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0002456|RO:0002178 some UBERON:0002370|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0002456|UBERON:0004573

name: thyroid vein
description: A vein that drains a thyroid gland.

name: meningeal vein
description: One of the veins draining a meninix.

name: internal pudendal vein
description: Accompanying vein of internal pudendal artery.

name: external pudendal vein
description: One of the veins of the pelvis which drain into the great saphenous vein.

name: jejunal artery
description: A branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the jejunum.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0001182|RO:0002178 some UBERON:0002115|RO:0002380 some UBERON:0001182|UBERON:0004573

name: lacrimal vein
description: A vein that drains a lacrimal gland.

name: layer of muscle tissue
description: Any organ component layer that consists of muscle tissue.

name: anterior root of zygomatic arch
description: The anterior or rostral end of the zygomatic arch, which includes the temporal process of the zygomatic bone, but also including some of the body of the zygomatic bone. It may also include the zygomatico-temporal suture and the most rostral portion of the zygomatic process of the temporal bone.

name: third phalanx
description: The third phalangeal bone in a digit ray.

name: atlantal spinal nerve foramen
description: Foramen housing the root of the spinal nerve seen in the neural arch of the first vertebrae (atlas). (see Edwards 1976).

name: type 1 adrenal tissue
description: Adrenal tissue dispersed in clusters, found in periphery and center of adrenal gland in turtles (Yadav, 2008).

name: type 2 adrenal tissue
description: Adrenal tissue aggregated in a dorsal layer covering internal cords, found in lepidosaur adrenal glands. Islets of adrenal tissue found on ventral surface of gland (barely present in squamates). See Yadav, 2008.

name: type 3 adrenal tissue
description: Adrenal tissue found in archosaurs - tissue arranged in bands, alternating with interrenal cords (Yadav, 2008).

name: type 4 adrenal tissue
description: In mammals, adrenal tissue has a cortex and medulla creating a composite adrenal gland (Kardong 2012).

name: apex of paracone
description: The highest elevation of the paracone on a molariform tooth.

name: caniniform region
description: The anterior region of the maxillary tooth row, if that tooth row contains teeth that are substantially over the premaxillary teeth (see Laurin and Reisz 1995).

name: postcingulum of deciduous premolar 5
description: A postcingulum found on deciduous premolar 5.

name: posthypocrista of deciduous premolar 5
description: A posthypocrista found on deciduous premolar 5.

name: calcareous egg tooth
description: Tooth used to break the eggshell, that is shed soon after hatching. In lepidosaurs, a true tooth that is shed soon after hatching.

name: hypoconid
description: The labial most of three cusps on the talonoid (posterior) end of lower molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: lower deciduous premolar 5
description: Fifth premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.

name: lower molar 3
description: Third molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the lower jaw.

name: lower pharyngobranchial toothplate
description: Pharyngeal toothplate of the lower jaw region; typically associated with ceratobranchial 5 element.

name: lower premolar 1
description: First premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.

name: lower premolar 2
description: Second premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.

name: molar 1 posteroloph
description: Posteroloph found on the first molar tooth.

name: premolar 1 hypoconoid
description: Hypoconid found on the first premolar tooth.

name: paracone
description: The anterior cusp along the labial margin seen in the molar or premolar teeth of mammals. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: paracristid
description: A crest running along the labial margin of molarifomr teeth of mammals. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: postcingulum
description: A shelf like ridge on the posterior (distal) outside edge of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: posteroloph
description: A shelf like ridge on the outside of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: posthypocrista
description: A crest on the hypoconid of molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: precingulum
description: A shelf like ridge on the proximal (mesial) outside edge of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/).

name: premolar 1
description: First premolar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the jaw.

name: preprotocrista
description: An enamel ridge joining the protocone and the paracone on the occlusal surface of a maxillary molar.

name: replacement tooth
description: Tooth (often obscured from view) in a 'waiting' position that will replace an existing tooth (i.e. a tooth that is well visible in the jaw).

name: resorption pit
description: A pit formed in an existing functional tooth, causing resorption of the surrounding dentine and periodontal tissues. (modified from LeBlanc and Reisz 2013, see figures 8, 10 for more details).

name: stylocone
description: Cusp found on a platform that is buccaal and mesial to the meta and paracones. Modified from Kermack 1967. Molar evolution in Mesozoic mammals.

name: mandibular symphyseal tooth
description: Tooth of the lower jaw that is adjacent to the mandibular symphysis.
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0018542|RO:0002220 some UBERON:0006606|RO:0002371 some UBERON:0004768|UBERON:0003268|UBERON:0004756

name: upper canine 1
description: First canine (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.

name: upper deciduous premolar 5
description: Fifth premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the upper jaw.

name: upper molar 1
description: First molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.

name: adrenal tissue
description: Tissue that is part of some adrenal gland.

name: post-axial region of pectoral appendage
description: Anatomical region lying to the posteiror or ventral side of the metapterygial axis.

name: bicipital surface
description: Region of the humerus associated with the biceps attachment areas.

name: keel
description: Ridge shaped projection, similar to the keel of a boat.

name: caudal melanophore spot
description: Distinct colored area on the caudal region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.

name: central figure of scute
description: Anatomical structure consisting of a pattern of ridges on an osteoderm.

name: cephalic dermal scale
description: A dermal scale that is found in the head region.

name: cheek scale
description: A scale part of the cheek scale row.

name: cheek scale row
description: A row of scales foudn in the cheek region of the head of an organism.

name: choanal groove
description: Grooves on the palatine bone which denote the passage of the choana or internal naris.

name: clasper plate
description: Pelvic clasper organs that have been modified into a flattened structure.

name: cuboid facet of calcaneum
description: Facet on the anterior surface of the calcaneus (as called calcaneum) for the articulation of the cuboid bone.

name: dorsal osteoderm
description: Osteoderm found on the dorsal surface of an organisms.

name: entocarotid fossa
description: A depression on the lateral surface of the braincase posterior to the Vidian canal (Conrad 2008).

name: extramural oviduct
description: Section of the oviduct external to the uterine wall.

name: flexor sesamoid
description: A sesamoid bone located near or in the flexor musculature of a joint.

name: foramen for glossopharyngeal nerve
description: Foramen that allows the passge of the glossopharyngeal nerve (cranial nerve IX).

name: fourth phalanx
description: Fourth most proximal phalanx in manual or pedal digits.

name: hyoid articular area
description: Area on the otic capsule for the articulation of the hyoid.

name: hypochordal radial
description: Caudal fin radial element located ventral to the notochord.

name: ilioischiadic foramen
description: Situated just caudal to the acetabulum, the foramen is bound dorsally by the illium and ventrally by the ischium. The foramen transmitts the ischiadic nerves and vessels (Baumel et al. 1993).
parents: BFO:0000050 some UBERON:0007832|RO:0002220 some UBERON:0001273|RO:0002220 some UBERON:0001274|UBERON:0004120|UBERON:0005744|obo:uberon/core#conduit_for some UBERON:0001322

name: incisura fossa
description: The condyloid fossa on the cranial aspect of the Atlas my be perforated (foramen fossa) or have an open dorsal notch (Incisura fossa) in which the apex of the dens rides. (From Baumel et al. 1993).

name: interpterygoid vacuity
description: Open space between on the palate between the pteryogoid bone and the parasphenoid.

name: intraramal joint
description: A joint in the lower jaw that enhances kinesis and for swallowing prey. Allows enhanced mobility and intraramal bending to increase gape.

name: jugal bar
description: Elongate bar consisting of fused quadratojugal and jugal and connecting the maxilla to the quadrate.
parents: RO:0002176 some UBERON:0002397|RO:0002176 some UBERON:0006597|RO:0002374 some UBERON:0001683|RO:0002374 some UBERON:0011267|UBERON:0005913

name: labial cartilage
description: Distinct cartilage around the jaws of elasmobranchs.

name: lateral condyle of quadrate
description: Condyle on the lateral side of the quadrate.

name: lateral dorsal aorta canal
description: One of the branches of the dorsal aorta, after it enters the aortic canal.

name: maxillary shank
description: The triangular shaped posterior fold at the angle of the mouth. From Chakrabarty 2006.

name: medial condyle of quadrate
description: The medialmost condyle on the distal region of the quadrate, in contact with the pterygoid.

name: medial cotyla
description: The medialmost of the cotyla of the lower jaw, for articulation with the cranium.

name: metotic fissure
description: An embryonic fissure between the otic capsule and the arches which develop into the occipital bones. The fissure may persist into adulthood. It is also referred to as the 'lateral otic fissure' The metotic fissure opens into the vestibular fontanelle, if the fontanelle is present. (Johanson et al. (2003)). Otherwise it opens to the metotic foramen.

name: midbody melanophore spot
description: Distinct colored area on the midbody region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.

name: nasal process of premaxilla
description: A bony projection of the premaxilla that extends cadually and separates the nasal bones.

name: nuchal hump
description: Dorsal swelling on the head. Found in cichlid fish. Often only in males and during breeding season, but not exclusively so.

name: oviduct mucosal fold
description: The wall of the fallopian tube includes an elaborately folded mucosa (endosalpinx) surrounded by a muscularis (myosalpinx). The mucosa is lined by a ciliated columnar epithelium with secretory cells, and is folded out into the lumen so that an ovum in the lumen will always be close to the cilia for transport to the uterus.

name: parastyle
description: An anterior cusp on the stylar shelf of the tooth.

name: parietal notch
description: A pronounced notch or cavity in the lateral face of the parietal.

name: pharyngeal apophysis
description: Ventral process on the neurocranium for the articulation of upper pharyngeal bones. It is variably composed of the parasphenoid, basioccipital, and prootic depending on the species. From: Greenwood, PH (1978). A review of the pharyngeal hypophysis and its significance in the classification of African cichlid fishes. Bull. Br. Mus. Nat. Hist. (Zool.) 33: 297-323.

name: precerebral fontanelle
description: The lack of chondrification of the anterior wall of the cranial cavity in front of the pineal foramen.....(Hanken and Hall).

name: prismatic cartilage
description: Cartilage arranged into tesserae, blocks of calcified cartilage that fit together as tiles on a floor form a mosaic. Found only in chondrichthyans. Reference: A. Peter Klimley. 2013. The Biology of Sharks and Rays. University of Chicago Press.

name: quadrate condyle
description: The convex articular surface on the qudrate, part of the craniomandibular joint.

name: recessus vena jugularis
description: As defined here, this refers to a depression on the lateral surface of the braincase posterior to the Vidian canal as opposed to the carotid fossa...(Conrad 2008).

name: rictal bristle
description: Rictal bristles project from the beak of many insect-eating birds, including flycatchers, nightjars and even the American Robin. They are believed to provide protection for the bird's eyes as it consumes its wriggly prey. The bristles may also provide tactile feedback, like the whiskers on a dog or cat. from http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/studying/feathers/feathers/document_view.

name: rostral entotympanic element
description: An entotympanic that arises in forward part of tympanic floor. It may be intimately fused witA cartilage of tube during development(MacPhee (1981: 62)) in contrast to a caudal entotympanic arising in the rear tympanic floor. From O'Leary et al. 2012.

name: spina externa
description: A median bony point projecting from the anterior and ventral margin of the sternum of a bird. From http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/spina%20externa.

name: subolfactory process
description: The ventral portion of the frontals which forms part of the lateral wall of the braincase. Modified from Lee and Caldwell 1998.

name: suborbital foramen
description: Foramen located below the orbit and forming a passageway for nerves (eg fifth cranial nerve).

name: suborbital shelf
description: On the neurocranium, a horizontal plate arising on the ventral junction of the orbital wall and basal plate on each side which extends from the nasal capsule to the otic capsule; it forms the floor of the orbit.

name: supracondylar tubercle
description: Anatomical projection on the distal region of the femur or humerus and close to the condyles.

name: suprameatal foramen
description: Foramen in the temporal bone, adjacent to the base of the zygomatic process.

name: supratemporal process
description: Process of the parietal.

name: supratendinal bridge
description: Ossified bridge over a tendon; Particularly, the bridge over the extensor canal at the distal end of the tibiotarsus of certain birds. The presence of the bridge and the position of the canal opening relative to the condyles may have phylogenetic significance. Ericson (1997). http://palaeos.com/vertebrates/glossary/glossarySq.html.

name: processus ventralis of thoracic vertebra
description: The crest is present on the ventral side of the bodies of the thoracic vertebra (modified from Baumel et al. 1993).

name: processus ventrolateralis of thoracic vertebra
description: Ventrolaerally oriented, paired projections atttached to the ventrolateral border of the body of certain thoracic vertebra; the ventrolateral crest flank the crista ventralis on each side. From Baumel et al. 1993.

name: upper lateral line
description: Dorsal sensory canal line in fish, dorsal to ventral lateral lane.

name: ventral lateral line
description: Ventral sensory canal line in fish, ventral to dorsal lateral lane.

name: ventral supracondylar tubercle
description: Tubercle on the distal humerus for the origin of the Lig. collaterale ventral of the elbow joint. Modified from Baumel et al. 1993.

name: vidian canal
description: Canal for the vidian nerve.

name: sallet
description: A unit of the tectoral membrane that is shaped like string of flat, pearls. Modified from Manley, Fey and Popper 2008 .

name: molar tooth 1
description: The molar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 1.

name: molar tooth 3
description: The molar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 3.

name: metacestode
description: The larval (metacestode) stage of the tapeworm Echinococcus multilocularis.

name: second instar larva
description: Instar: a stage in the life of an arthropod (as an insect) between two successive molts.

name: metacercaria
description: A tailless encysted late larva of a trematode parasite that is usually the form which is infective for the definitive host.

name: cercaria
description: A usually tadpole-shaped larval trematode worm that develops in a molluscan host from a redia.

name: interoceptor
description: A sensory receptor that detects stimulus within the body. Examples of stimuli that would be detected by interoceptors include blood pressure and blood oxygen level.

name: chemoreceptor
description: A sensory receptor that detects chemical stimulus within the body.

name: posterior superior alveolar artery
description: The posterior superior alveolar artery (posterior dental artery) is given off from the maxillary, frequently in conjunction with the infraorbital just as the trunk of the vessel is passing into the pterygopalatine fossa.

name: posterior superior alveolar nerve
description: The posterior superior alveolar branches (posterior superior dental branches) arise from the trunk of the maxillary nerve just before it enters the infraorbital groove; they are generally two in number, but sometimes arise by a single trunk. They descend on the tuberosity of the maxilla and give off several twigs to the gums and neighboring parts of the mucous membrane of the cheek. They then enter the posterior alveolar canals on the infratemporal surface of the maxilla, and, passing from behind forward in the substance of the bone, communicate with the middle superior alveolar nerve, and give off branches to the lining membrane of the maxillary sinus and gingival and dental branches to each molar tooth from a superior dental plexus; these branches enter the apical foramina at the roots of the teeth. The posterior superior alveolar nerve innervates the second and third maxillary molars, and two of the three roots of the maxillary first molar (all but the mesiobuccal root). When giving a Posterior Superior Alveolar nerve block, it will anesthetize the mesialbuccal root of the maxillary first molar approximately 72% of the time.

name: mental nerve
description: Mental nerve is a general somatic afferent (sensory) nerve which provides sensation to the anterior aspects of the chin and lower lip as well as the buccal gingivae of the mandibular anterior teeth and the premolars. It is a branch of the posterior trunk of the inferior alveolar nerve, which is itself a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V). The nerve emerges at the mental foramen in the mandibula, and divides beneath the Depressor anguli oris muscle into three branches: one descends to the skin of the chin. two ascend to the skin and mucous membrane of the lower lip. These branches communicate freely with the facial nerve.

name: infra-orbital foramen of maxilla
description: A foramen on the exterior of the maxilla that is continuous with the infra-orbital canal and is the conduit for the passage of the infraorbital nerve and artery.

name: infra-orbital nerve
description: A branch of the maxillary nerve that enters the infraorbital canal and innervates the lower eyelid, upper lip, the nasal vestibule, the upper incisors, canines, premolars, upper gums, lower eyelid and conjunctiva, and part of the nose.

name: infra-orbital groove of maxilla
description: A groove on the interior of the maxilla that is continuous with the infra-orbital canal and is the conduit for the passage of the infraorbital nerve and artery.

name: lacteal
description: A lymphatic capillary that absorbs dietary fats in the villi of the small intestine.

name: ligament of hip joint
description: A skeletal ligament that is part of a hip joint.

name: vidian nerve
description: A nerve that is formed by the junction of the great petrosal nerve and the deep petrosal nerve and continues on to innervate the palate, nose and lacrimal gland.

name: facial nerve canal
description: A Z-shaped canal running through the temporal bone from the internal acoustic meatus to the stylomastoid foramen. It is located within the middle ear region, according to its shape it is divided into three main segments: the labyrinthine, the tympanic, and the mastoidal segment .

name: petrosal foramen
description: A foramen of skull that is part of a petrosal bone.

name: foramen of nasal bone
description: A vascular foramen opening on the outer surface of a nasal bone.

name: female inguinal ring
description: An inguinal ring that is part of a female reproductive system.

name: male inguinal ring
description: An inguinal ring that is part of a male reproductive system.

name: female superficial inguinal ring
description: A deep inguinal ring that is part of a female reproductive system.

name: female deep inguinal ring
description: A deep inguinal ring that is part of a male reproductive system.

name: mandibular symphyseal region
description: The region of the mandible on or near the midline (near the mandiblular symphysis).

name: lumen of intestine
description: The anatomical space within the intestine.

name: trigeminal nerve muscle
description: Muscle innervated by the trigeminal nerve (Cranial Nerve V).

name: nucleus of the bulbocavernosus
description: A cluster of motoneurons located in the anterior gray column of lumbar segments 5 and 6 of the spinal cord in the rat. Functionally it belongs to the somatic motoneuron pools of the subcortical motor system ( Swanson-2004 ).

name: ventral wall of dorsal aorta
description: Region where blood progenitor markers are expressed. Probable site of definitive hematopoiesis between 36hpf and 4dpf.

name: upper secondary canine tooth
description: A secondary canine tooth that is part of a upper jaw region.

name: lower secondary canine tooth
description: A secondary canine tooth that is part of a lower jaw region.

name: lower central secondary incisor tooth
description: A lower jaw incisor that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition.

name: lower lateral secondary incisor tooth
description: A lower jaw incisor that is in_the_lateral_side_of a dentition.

name: upper primary incisor tooth
description: A primary incisor tooth that is part of a upper jaw region.

name: upper central primary incisor tooth
description: A upper primary canine tooth that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition.

name: upper lateral primary incisor tooth
description: A upper primary canine tooth that is in_the_lateral_side_of a dentition.

name: lower central primary incisor tooth
description: A lower primary incisor tooth that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition.

name: lower lateral primary incisor tooth
description: A lower primary incisor tooth that is in_the_lateral_side_of a dentition.

name: upper primary canine tooth
description: A primary canine tooth that is part of a upper jaw region.

name: lower primary canine tooth
description: A primary canine tooth that is part of a lower jaw region.

name: lower central incisor tooth
description: An incisor tooth that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition and is part of a lower jaw region.

name: lower lateral incisor tooth
description: An incisor tooth that is in_the_lateral_side_of a dentition and is part of a lower jaw region.

name: upper central incisor tooth
description: An incisor tooth that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition and is part of a upper jaw region.

name: upper lateral incisor tooth
description: An incisor tooth that is in_the_lateral_side_of a dentition and is part of a upper jaw region.

name: molar tooth 2
description: The molar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 2.

name: foramen lacerum
description: A triangular hole in the base of the skull located at the base of the medial pterygoid plate.

name: anterior ethmoidal foramen
description: The anterior ethmoidal foramen, situated about the middle of the lateral margin of the olfactory groove, transmits the anterior ethmoidal vessels and the anterior ethmoidal nerve; the nerve runs in a groove along the lateral edge of the cribriform plate to the slit-like opening above mentioned.

name: posterior ethmoidal foramen
description: The posterior ethmoidal foramen opens at the back part of this margin under cover of the projecting lamina of the sphenoid, and transmits the posterior ethmoidal vessels and nerve.

name: puparium
description: A chitin-based cuticular shell derived from the cuticle of the final larval instar that surrounds the pupal form of the organism.

name: heart vasculature
description: An interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure that contains fluid that is actively transported around the heart.

name: pelvic splanchnic nerve
description: A splanchnic nerves that arises from sacral spinal nerves S2, S3, S4 to provide parasympathetic innervation to the hindgut.

name: renal nerve plexus
description: The renal plexus is formed by filaments from the celiac plexus, the aorticorenal ganglion, and the aortic plexus . It is joined also by the least splanchnic nerve. The nerves from these sources, fifteen or twenty in number, have a few ganglia developed upon them. They accompany the branches of the renal artery into the kidney; some filaments are distributed to the spermatic plexus and, on the right side, to the inferior vena cava.

name: thoracic splanchnic nerve
description: Thoracic splanchnic nerves are splanchnic nerves that arise from the sympathetic trunk in the thorax and travel inferiorly to provide sympathetic innervation to the abdomen. The nerves contain preganglionic sympathetic and general visceral afferent fibers.

name: lumbar splanchnic nerve
description: The lumbar splanchnic nerves are splanchnic nerves that arise from the lumbar part of the sympathetic trunk and travel to an adjacent plexus near the aorta. They are originated from L1 and L2. These nerves contain preganglionic sympathetic and visceral afferent fibers. The site of synapse is found in the prevertebral ganglia and innervate the smooth muscle and glands of the pelvic viscera and hindgut.

name: sacral splanchnic nerve
description: A splanchnic nerve that connects the inferior hypogastric plexus to the sympathetic trunk in the pelvis.

name: glial limiting membrane
description: The meshwork of astrocytic foot processes (glial end feet) covered by a basal lamina adjacent to the inner pial surface of the central nervous system.

name: bladder organ
description: A membranous sac in animals that serves as the receptacle of a liquid or contains gas.

name: intramuscular adipose tissue
description: Adipose tissue which is located throughout skeletal muscle and is responsible for the marbling seen in certain cuts of beef. In humans, excess accumulation of intramuscular fat is associated with insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes.

name: dorsal nerve of penis
description: The deep terminal division of the pudendal nerve that runs along the dorsum of the penis and innervates the the corpus cavernosum penis, the prepuce and the glans penis.

name: dorsal nerve of clitoris
description: The deep terminal division of the pudendal nerve that runs along the dorsum of the clitoral shaft and innervates the the glans clitoris.

name: skin of anterior chest
description: Zone of skin that is part of the anterior region of the chest.

name: gemellus muscle
description: One of the two small muscular fasciculi, accessories to the tendon of the Obturator internus which is received into a groove between them.

name: inferior gemellus muscle
description: Gemellus muscle that arises from the upper part of the tuberosity of the ischium, immediately below the groove for the Obturator internus tendon. It blends with the lower part of the tendon of the Obturator internus, and is inserted with it into the medial surface of the greater trochanter.

name: superior gemellus muscle
description: The smaller of the two gemellus muscles that arises from the outer surface of the spine of the ischium, blends with the upper part of the tendon of the Obturator internus, and is inserted with it into the medial surface of the greater trochanter[WP].

name: skin epithelium
description: Any region of epithelium that is part of a skin region.

name: anterior pole of lens
description: The central point on the anterior surface of the lens.

name: pole of lens
description: A central point or region on the anterior or posterior surface of the lens.

name: white matter of hindbrain
description: A white matter that is part of the hindbrain.

name: white matter of forebrain
description: A white matter that is part of the forebrain.

name: white matter of myelencephalon
description: A white matter that is part of the myelencephalon.

name: uncinate fasciculus of the forebrain
description: A fiber pathway in the cerebral white matter that connects anterior portions of the temporal lobe with the inferior frontal gyrus and the middle frontal gyrus. It is not readily distinguished in myelin-stained cross-sections (adapted from Brain Info).

name: epithelium of external nose
description: Epithelial layer that is part of the external part of the nose.

name: septohypothalamic nucleus
description: A group of cells located between the lateral septal nucleus and the anterior commissure in the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ). Some authors regard it as part of the lateral septal nucleus ( Swanson-1998 ).

name: root of olfactory nerve
description: The initial segment of an olfactory nerve, leaving the central nervous system.

name: precordial region
description: A subdivision of the trunk that is comprised of the epigastrium and the anterior lower thorax.

name: intraorbital lacrimal gland
description: A lacrimal gland located superficially at the lateral canthus, where both the lacrimal gland and Harderian gland ducts open.

name: exorbital lacrimal gland
description: A lacrimal gland located subcutaneously at the anteroventral base of the ear adjacent to the parotid gland.

name: lobe of lacrimal gland
description: An anatomical lobe that is part of a lacrimal gland.

name: orbital lobe of lacrimal gland
description: Larger of the two lacrimal gland lobes located superficially.

name: palpebral lobe of lacrimal gland
description: Smaller of the two lacrimal gland lobes located at the eyelid.

name: accessory XI nerve nucleus
description: The spinal accessory nucleus lies within the cervical spinal cord (C1-C5) in the ventral horn. The nucleus ambiguus is classically said to provide the 'cranial component' of the accessory nerve. However, the very existence of this cranial component has been recently questioned and seen as contributing exclusively to the vagus nerve. The terminology continues to be used in describing both human anatomy, and that of other animals.

name: auricular blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that supplies or drains an ear.

name: superior longitudinal fasciculus
description: The superior longitudinal fasciculus (also called the superior longitudinal fascicle or SLF) is a pair of long bi-directional bundles of neurons connecting the front and the back of the cerebrum. Each association fiber bundle is lateral to the centrum ovale of a cerebral hemisphere and connects the frontal, occipital, parietal, and temporal lobes. The neurons pass from the frontal lobe through the operculum to the posterior end of the lateral sulcus where numerous neurons radiate into the occipital lobe and other neurons turn downward and forward around the putamen and radiate to anterior portions of the temporal lobe.

name: precentral sulcus
description: The precentral sulcus lies parallel to, and in front of, the central sulcus. (A sulcus is one of the prominent grooves on the surface of the human brain. ) The precentral sulcus divides the inferior, middle, and superior frontal gyri from the precentral gyrus. In the majority of brains, the precentral sulcus is divided into two parts: the inferior precentral sulcus and the superior precentral sulcus. However, the precentral sulcus may also be divided into three parts or form one continuous sulcus.

name: ventral thalamic fasciculus
description: The thalamic fasciculus is a component of the subthalamus. It is sometimes considered synonymous with 'field H1 of Forel'. Nerve fibres forming a composite bundle containing cerebellothalamic (crossed) and pallidothalamic (uncrossed) fibres that is insinuated between the thalamus and zona incerta. The thalamic fasciculus consists of the joint fibers of the ansa lenticularis and the lenticular fasciculus, coming from different portions of the medial globus pallidus, before they jointly enter the ventral lateral nucleus of the thalamus.

name: subthalamic fasciculus
description: The subthalamic fasciculus is a tract which connects the subthalamic nucleus and the globus pallidus. It is a bidirectional connection between the GP and the subthalamic nucleus, including (1) fibers running from the GPe to the subthalamic nucleus, and (2) fibers running from the STN back to the GP.

name: auditory radiation
description: The acoustic radiations or auditory radiations are structures found in the brain, in the ventral cochlear pathway, a part of the auditory system. Lesions to the auditory radiations could be a cause of cortical deafness.

name: optic radiation
description: The optic radiation (also known as the geniculo-calcarine tract or as the geniculostriate pathway) is a collection of axons from relay neurons in the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus carrying visual information to the visual cortex (also called striate cortex) along the calcarine fissure. There is one such tract on each side of the brain.

name: planum temporale
description: The planum temporale is the cortical area just posterior to the auditory cortex within the Sylvian fissure. It is a triangular region which forms the heart of Wernicke's area, one of the most important functional areas for language. The planum temporale shows a significant asymmetry. In 65% of all individuals the left planum temporale appears to be more developed, while the right planum temporale is more developed in only 10%. In some peoplebs brains, the planum temporale is more than five times larger on the left than on the right, making it the most asymmetrical structure in the brain. This greater size of the left planum temporale compared with the right is already present in the foetus, where it can be observed starting from the 31st week of gestation. This observation strengthens the hypothesis of a genetic predisposition for brain asymmetry.

name: corticopontine fibers
description: Corticopontine fibers, commonly referred to as corticobulbar fibers, are projections from the cerebral cortex to the pontine nuclei. Depending upon the lobe of origin, they can be classified as frontopontine fibers, parietopontine fibers, temporopontine fibers and occipitopontine fibers. They are motor fibers that stretch from the precentral gyrus (motor strip) to the nuclei of cranial nerves V (trigenimal), VII (facial) and XII (hypoglossal). These fibers run alongside the corticospinal fibers.

name: corticobulbar tract
description: The corticobulbar (or corticonuclear) tract is a white matter pathway connecting the cerebral cortex to the brainstem. The term 'bulbar' refers to the brainstem, as 'bulb' was a historical term meaning the area currently called the brainstem. The 'bulb' is an archaic term for the medulla oblongata. In clinical usage, it includes the pons as well.

name: lacrimal lake
description: A small cistern-like area of the conjunctiva at the medial angle of the eye, in which the tears collect after bathing the front surface of the eyeball and the conjunctival sac.

name: lacrimal papilla
description: A small conical elevation at the basal angle of the lacrimal lake.

name: colic flexure
description: A sharp bend between consecutive segments of the colon.

name: splenic flexure of colon
description: The splenic (or left colic) flexure is a sharp bend between the transverse and the descending colon in the left upper quadrant of humans. The left colic flexure is near the spleen, and hence called the splenic flexure. There are two colic flexures in the transverse colon — the other being the hepatic flexure in the right upper quadrant.

name: hepatic flexure of colon
description: Hepatic (or the right colic) flexure is the sharp bend between the ascending and the transverse colon. The right colic flexure is adjacent to the liver, and is therefore also known as the hepatic flexure. Thus, the left colic flexure is also known as the splenic flexure (as it is close to the spleen). The hepatic flexure lies in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen in humans.

name: nucleus of pudendal nerve
description: A nucleus in the ventral part of the anterior horn of the sacral region of the spinal cord that is the origin of the pudendal nerve.

name: pineal recess of third ventricle
description: The diverticulum of the thin roof of the dorsocaudal third ventricle that projects into the stalk of the pineal gland.

name: lacrimal gland bud
description: The single bud-like invagination of the conjunctival fornix epithelium at the temporal aspect of the eye that signals lacrimal gland formation (Int Rev Cytol. 1996;168:1-80. Cell biology of the harderian gland).

name: strand of tylotrich hair
description: A single large hair, surrounded by neurovascular tissue at the level of the sebaceous gland, with a hair follicle innervated by a hair-tylotrich neuron (CL:1001436), a rapidly acting mechanoreceptor.

name: morphological boundary
description: A two dimensional anatomical structure that corresponds to some structural discontinuity.

name: inferior palpebral branch of infra-orbital nerve
description: A nerve that innervates a lower eyelid and is a branch of the infra-orbital branch of the maxillary nerve.

name: nasociliary nerve
description: A branch of the ophthalmic nerve that serves to supply the mucous membrane of the nose, the tip of the nose, and the conjunctiva.

name: long ciliary nerve
description: A branch of the nasociliary nerve that innervates the ciliary muscles, the iris, and the cornea.

name: short ciliary nerve
description: A branch of the ciliary ganglion that innervates the ciliary muscles, the iris, and the tunics of the eyeball.

name: nervous system cell part layer
description: Single layer of a laminar structure, identified by different density, arrangement or size of cells and processes arranged in flattened layers or lamina[CUMBO].

name: superior colliculus stratum zonale
description: Most superficial layer of the superior colliculus consisting primarily of thin fibers derived primarily from the occipital cortex (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 2nd 3d, 1981, pg. 544).

name: olfactory cortex layer 1
description: Surface layer of the olfactory cortex that contains dendrites, fiber systems and a small number of neurons. It has been divided into a superficial part and a deep part.

name: olfactory cortex layer 2
description: Middle layer of olfactory cortex lying deep to layer 1 and superficial to layer 3, characterized by a compact layer of cell bodies. It can be divided into a superficial part and a deep part.

name: lateral geniculate nucleus parvocellular layer
description: Layer of the lateral geniculate nucleus characterized by small cells (adapted from Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_geniculate_nucleus).

name: entorhinal cortex layer 4
description: Layer of entorhinal cortex lying superficial to layer 5 and deep to layer 3, that is relatively acellular. (Paxinos, The rat nervous system, Academic Press, 1995, pg 473-474).

description: Layer of entorhinal cortex lying superficial to layer 6 and deep to layer 4 characterized by large pyramidal neurons that are darkly stained in Nissl preparations (Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 474).

name: entorhinal cortex layer 3
description: Layer of the entorhinal cortex lying superficial to layer 4and deep to layer 2. It is characterized by cells of various sizes and shapes with a predominance of pyramidal cells (Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 474).

name: entorhinal cortex layer 6
description: Layer of entorhinal cortex lying superficial to the cerebral white matter and deep to layer 5 characterized by cells of various shapes and sizes (Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 474).

name: entorhinal cortex layer 1
description: Layer of the entorhinal cortex that is most superficial, continuous with layer 1 of adjacent neocortex and the molecular layer of the subiculum, lying deep to the pial layer and superficial to layer 2. It is relatively acellular consisting mostly of fibers running transversely relative to the cortical surface (Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 474).

name: entorhinal cortex layer 2
description: Layer of the entorhinal cortex lying superficial to layer 3 and deep to layer 1. It is characterized by medium-to large sized stellate cells that are grouped into prominent clusters, particularly in the rostral entorhinal cortex (Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 474).
